<FIRST>r a AM-ShootingTrek     03-18 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shooting Trek,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paterson Man Turns Himself In After Being Sought For Shooting Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who fled the shooting of his wife
crashed his car, took over two other vehicles at gunpoint and left
an abducted family beside a New York highway before surrendering
Friday, police said.
   Victor Otero, 39, was wanted for the Thursday night shooting of
his estranged wife, Evelyn Diaz Otero, 34. She was in critical
condition Friday night at St. Joseph's Medical Center, said a
nursing superviser.
   Otero turned himself in to Paterson police about 5 p.m. Friday
and was arrested on charges of attempted murder, kidnapping, armed
robbery and unlawful possession of a weapon, said police Sgt. Craig
Perrone.
   Otero was held in the city jail pending arraignment Saturday.
   Police said the shooting began an interstate trek across the
Hudson River and a manhunt that involved police from Paterson, New
York City and Nassau County.
   Otero shot his wife several times about 10:15 p.m. Thursday and
fled in his own car only to get into an accident with other cars a
few blocks away.
   Witnesses told police Otero pulled a revolver and forced Nelson
Vazquez of Paterson to drive him to New York City. Vazquez dropped
Otero off near the New York end of the Lincoln Tunnel in Manhattan,
police said.
   There, Otero approached a car stopped at a pay phone and forced
five members of a North Carolina family to drive him to Long Island,
said Officer Janice Swinney, a New York City police spokeswoman.
   A male family member was at a pay phone when Otero allegedly
forced him back into the car and made them drive to Long Island.
   ``I thought he was going to kill us for sure,'' said Bobby Gee,
whose husband, daughter, son, and grandson were held at gunpoint
during the two-hour ordeal.
   ``We started to pray out loud as soon as he got into the car,''
Mrs. Gee said. ``He told us to shut up.''
   The gunman forced the family, which was in New York to attend a
funeral service, out of the car on the Long Island Expressway near
Old Westbury, police said. Perrone said there were no reports of
injuries to the family or Vazquez.
   Otero then fled on foot. He contacted his relatives while on the
run and was talked into giving himself up, Perrone said.
</TEXT>
