<FIRST>r w PM-SteelImports     03-18 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Call for End to Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one senators have lined up against their
steel-state colleagues and called on President Bush to end steel
import quotas covering 19 nations and the European Community.
   The senators said in a letter Friday to Bush that the restraints
have driven up steel prices and caused product shortages. They said
the United States needed ``a sensible steel policy'' that considered
not just steelmakers, but other producers, too.
   The senators, 18 of them Republican, face stiff opposition.
Fifty-five other senators, many of them from steel-producing states,
have signed onto a bill empowering the Bush administration to extend
the import curbs beyond their Sept. 30 expiration.
   The Reagan administration negotiated five-year,
product-by-product ``voluntary restraint agreements'' in 1984 with
Japan, South Korea, Brazil, South Africa, the European Community and
other nations to limit the flow of foreign steel into the United
States.
   Three days before last November's election, Bush pledged to
continue the restraints in some form. But with the steel industry
newly profitable, opponents of the curbs _ led by a coalition of
U.S. manufacturers _ believe they can make a case for ending the
program, or at least narrowing its scope.
   Manufacturers of home appliances, construction and farm
machinery, industrial equipment, auto parts and other products all
rely on steel as a raw material, said the letter to Bush.
   ``In the experience of many of these manufacturers, steel
voluntary restraint agreements have caused higher prices and
shortages of some steel products, and are undermining their ability
to compete in international markets,'' the letter said.
   ``It is important that steel trade be considered from the
perspective of all U.S. manufacturers, not just the steel industry
alone,'' it said. The senators invited Bush to work with Congress to
end the ``burden'' of the quotas.
   But Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., a leading advocate of continued
restraints, said through a spokesman Friday that the conditions that
compelled steel firms to seek government aid in 1984 remain.
   ``There are still some senators who keep their heads in the sand
when it comes to the fact that countries have not discontinued their
unfair trading practices of dumping and subsidies,'' said Richard
Bryers, legislative director for Heinz.
   Signing the letter to Bush were Sens. Brock Adams, D-Wash.; Rudy
Boschwitz, R-Minn.; Conrad Burns, R-Mont.; John Chafee, R-R.I.; Thad
Cochran, R-Miss.; Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Slade Gorton, R-Wash.;
Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.; Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.; Nancy Kassebaum,
R-Kan.; Robert Kasten, R-Wis.; Herbert Kohl, D-Wis.; Trent Lott,
R-Miss.; Connie Mack, R-Fla.; James McClure, R-Idaho; Bob Packwood,
R-Ore.; Larry Pressler, R-S.D.; Steve Symms, R-Idaho; Malcolm
Wallop, R-Wyo.; John Warner, R-Va.; and Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
