<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Eastern-Congress     03-18 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Congress,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bills Aiding Striking Eastern Workers Bogged Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Eastern Airline's striking unions
are shrugging off their inability to prompt Congress to quickly
produce legislation aimed at helping the thousands of picketers.
   The two bills that the carrier's workers are pinning their hopes
on both bogged down on Friday _ at least temporarily _ as the Senate
began its two-week Easter recess.
   Union leaders said the delay would not be overly harmful to
strikers, who began their third week of picketing today. Labor
leaders said they are relying more heavily on two other strategies:
working in the bankruptcy courts, and seeking a buyer for the
grounded airline.
   ``We never indicated to any of our members that these bills were
a panacea, they would be passed quickly, or anything like that,''
William Winpisinger, president of the International Association of
Machinists, said in an interview.
   ``We told our pilots up front that things in the House would go
quickly but the Senate would be an uphill fight,'' said Henry A.
Duffy, president of The Air Line Pilots Association.
   The Eastern strike began when the airline's 8,500 machinists
walked off their jobs in a wage and benefit dispute and were
followed by the carrier's pilots and flight attendants.
   Senate Democrats scheduled a vote for April 5 _ the chamber's
second post-Easter day of business _ on whether to allow
consideration of a bill that would hand the government a role in
ending the walkout. Republicans have so far blocked action on the
measure, which would compel President Bush to name a special board
to recommend a way to end the strike.
   At the Senate Judiciary Committee, officials of Eastern's parent
company, Texas Air Corp., voiced opposition to a measure that would
up the ante for management. The bill, introduced by Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, would allow Eastern's creditors access to the
assets of Texas Air, which also owns Continental Airlines. Eastern
filed for protection from its creditors under the federal bankruptcy
code on March 9.
   Texas Air's associate general counsel, Elliott M. Seiden, told
the panel that the bill would be ``unfair, oppressive and
unconstitutional'' and would have dangerous repercussions throughout
the airline industry.
   ``In the future, no corporation could or would consider acquiring
a troubled airline, or starting a new airline ... because the risk
of failing could not be confined to the new venture itself,'' Seiden
told the senators.
   Both bills are considered long shots for enactment into law.
Administration officials have threatened a veto of the emergency
board bill.
   The bankruptcy revision measure has been questioned by several
lawmakers, including Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., chairman of the
judiciary panel, who said Friday that he wants to study how the
proposal would effect other airlines.
   Union leaders and their Democratic supporters have sought action
on the bills anyway, arguing that their efforts would at the very
least be good for strikers' morale.
</TEXT>
