<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-ForeignAgents     03-18 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Agents,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Keep PAC Money They Claim is Tainted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Democratic senators say they'll keep $8,000
in campaign contributions from an imported-car dealers' group, even
though both complained the organization is a foreign agent forbidden
to make such payments.
   Although the Auto Dealers and Drivers Free Trade PAC gave $5,000
to Sen. Bob Graham of Florida and $3,000 to Sen. Harry Reid of
Nevada last year, it also spent nearly $1 million to defeat them and
Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev.
   Those three senators, along with Sen. David Boren, D-Okla.,
signed a letter to the Justice Department asking it to investigate
whether the PAC ought to be registered as a foreign agent.
   If the organization were found to be a foreign agent operating
with foreign funds, spending that money to influence an American
election would be illegal.
   Nevertheless, neither Graham nor Reid plan to give the money back
unless the Justice Department tells them to do so, their spokesmen
said.
   ``I mean these guys are hypocrites,'' Tom Nemet, chairman of the
PAC, said Friday. ``They asked us for money to support them.''
   Nemet and Frank Glacken, the imported-auto dealer PAC's executive
director, deny they're working for foreigners.
   The PAC spent nearly $2.6 million last year on House and Senate
elections. Of that total, about 83 percent was spent to help
Republican candidates, according to figures compiled by the Federal
Election Commission.
   Nemet and Glacken said in a telephone interview from their office
in New York City that Reid, Bryan and Graham are trying to get even
because the group spent large amounts of money against them.
   Nemet and Glacken said the organization's funding comes entirely
from American citizens.
   Jean Neal, a spokeswoman for Bryan, acknowledged that Bryan was
``not thrilled'' that the PAC spent more than half a million dollars
against him. Ken Klein, a spokesman for Graham, said the Senator
would wait to see what the Justice Department decides. Craig Varoga,
spokesman for Reid, said only that the senator does not plan to give
back any money.
   Boren, who has neither been opposed by nor accepted money from
the group, signed the letter because his colleagues asked him to and
because he is opposed to the role political action committees in
general are playing in American politics, said spokesman John Deeken.
   Under federal law, individuals or firms representing foreign
governments, people or companies have to register with the Justice
Department as foreign agents and report what activities they have
carried out for their clients.
   While foreign agents could still give money to political
campaigns as individual American citizens, the law does not permit
them to make such contributions in their role as foreign agents.
   The PAC also paid out big money to help Trent Lott in
Mississippi, Connie Mack in Florida and Malcolm Wallop in Wyoming.
All three of those Republicans won their Senate elections.
   Lott had $319,126 spent on his behalf by the PAC, Mack received a
$10,000 contribution and had another $326,050 spent for him, and
Wallop got a $4,000 contribution with $88,862 spent on his behalf,
according to the FEC.
   The PAC also spent money independently on two House races, and
the beneficiaries there were Democrats.
   Rep. David Skaggs of Colorado had $80,000 spent independently for
him, and Rep. Richard Stallings of Idaho got $45,000 spent
independently on his behalf.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
