<FIRST>r w PM-Flight103-Skinner     03-18 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103-Skinner,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Sending Aides to Europe for Flight 103 Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Flight 103 Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner says he
is sending top aides to Europe this weekend to look into the safety
of U.S. airlines and new allegations about warnings of terrorist
attack before the bombing of Flight 103.
   Skinner said Friday his action was prompted by a meeting with
relatives of some of the 270 people killed in the Dec. 21 disaster
over Scotland and by the controversy erupting in England over
specific threats before the bombing.
   In addition to dispatching members of his personal staff, Skinner
said he planned to visit England, France and West Germany himself
next month in an effort to get a united approach to the threat of
sky terrorism and find out more about the bombing and the warnings.
   The secretary said in a speech that his meeting with relatives of
some of the people killed in the Pan Am explosion convinced him he
must get directly involved in issues surrounding the bombing.
   Skinner said the relatives introduced themselves one by one,
using the names of loved ones killed in the crash.
   ``It was one of the most moving meetings I think I have ever had
... You were literally speechless,'' he said.
   Bert Ammerman, a victim's relative who attended the meeting,
praised Skinner for meeting with about 20 families but said he is
angry that the government has done so little to prevent further
terrorist attacks or warn passengers.
   He said neither former President Reagan nor President Bush has
sent even a note of condolence to any of the families, while at
least two U.S. victims' families received sympathy notes from
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   ``If we'd won the Super Bowl, we'd have been in the Rose Garden.
But if you get people blown out of the air, that's not important
enough,'' said Ammerman, whose brother was killed in the bombing.
   A group of Flight 103 victims' relatives proposes that the
government set up a telephone number passengers can call to see if
there are threats against a flight they are planning to take.
   Officials in England disclosed that a bomb warning, including a
photograph of a radio-cassette bomb of the type investigators
believe was used, was dated two days before the Pan Am 747 was
destroyed but did not reach the airlines until several days later.
   Both British authorities and the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration had described such a bomb in security warnings a
month earlier, airline and government officials said. The West
German intelligence agency said it sent a memo about the possibility
of such a bomb to U.S. airlines even earlier, on Nov. 10.
   Skinner said he was trying to get more details on the warning and
how they were handled.
   ``Let me tell you I don't know everything,'' he said. ``Yesterday
I learned some things for the first time, and I think the FAA did,
about some disclosures in West Germany as well as some possible
disclosures to United Kingdom airlines.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., chairman of a Senate
transportation subcommittee, introduced a resolution urging Bush to
appoint a commission to investigate the bombing.
   ``The FAA specifically warned that the explosive device might
evade detection by X-ray machines,'' Lautenberg said in a Senate
speech. ``We need to know what Pan Am and other airlines did, if
anything, in response to these warnings.''
   Lautenberg attempted to get floor passage of his resolution, but
Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming, the deputy Republican leader, said it
should go through the committee hearing process first.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
