<FIRST>r w PM-DC-Curfew     03-18 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-Curfew,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Says ACLU ``Out of Touch'' in Curfew Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit by the American Civil Liberties Union
challenging an emergency curfew for teen-agers in the nation's
capital shows the organization has lost touch with the reality of
drugs and violence, Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr. says.
   Barry commented Friday after the local ACLU chapter asked a
federal court to declare the District of Columbia's 90-day law
unconstitutional and issue an injunction blocking enforcement.
   Backers say the law is intended to help fight drugs in the
nation's capital by keeping people under 18 off city streets late at
night and early in the morning and thus away from the often violent
open-air drug markets.
   The class-action suit, filed in U.S. District Court on behalf of
the parents of five teen-agers, a 12-year-old boy and three other
people, says the curfew violates constitutional protection of
freedom of speech and association. The law also is flawed because it
forces young adults to carry adequate identification and display it
to police on request, and discriminates ``irrationally'' between
people under and over age 18.
   But Barry countered: ``The ACLU lawyers don't live in these
neighborhoods where you can't sleep at night because gunshots,
killings are going on. They don't live in communities where drugs
are being used or sold. They're out of touch with reality.''
   The emergency law went into effect Thursday. Enforcement will
start on Monday, the mayor said. The measure generally requires
people under age 18 to be off the streets by 11 p.m. during the week
and by midnight on weekends. The curfew ends daily at 6 a.m.
   The suit said one of the plaintiffs is a 17-year-old girl, Simbi
Waters, an actress attending art school who would need to be out
after midnight if she gets the part in a play for which she is now
auditioning.
   Another plaintiff, 17-year-old David Dranitzke, is a student
council president who attends senior class dinners at night about
twice a month and who says the senior prom this spring will last
well past midnight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
