<FIRST>r w PM-Quayle-Architect     03-18 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle-Architect,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested for Phony Credentials Worked On VP Residence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington businessman who had been asked by
Marilyn Quayle to design renovations for the vice presidential
residence was arrested on felony charges of misrepresenting himself
as a certified architect.
   Charles Scott Hughes, 36, was charged after he allegedly
fabricated the architect's seal on blueprints for renovation of
restrooms in Arlington County, Va., parks, said county police
detective William Cowell.
   Police said Hughes, who was arrested Tuesday, was not a licensed
architect but that he allegedly had fake District of Columbia and
Maryland architect's seals.
   Hughes, owner of Charles Scott Hughes and Associated Architects,
refused to comment on Friday, according to The Washington Post. His
attorney, Amy Berman, told the Post she would not comment on Hughes'
arrest or his business dealings.
   Hughes has not yet entered a plea in court.
   David Beckwith, a spokesman for Vice President Dan Quayle, said
Hughes and a former employee met with Quayle twice in the weeks
before Quayle moved into the official vice president's residence.
   Hughes toured the mansion and later submitted applications for
the $200,000 remodeling plan, said Beckwith. But he was never paid
the $5,000 fee he was due after submitting blueprints and plans
because the Secret Service found ``problems'' in his security
application and seized the plans.
</TEXT>
