<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-18 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Fails to Extend AZT Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has failed to extend a program that
provides the drug AZT to victims of AIDS who cannot afford the
costly treatment, virtually assuring that the program will expire
March 31.
   A bill sponsored by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., sought to
redirect $5 million in federal AIDS research funds to the AZT
program for use through September.
   But three senators objected to Kennedy's request on Friday that
the measure be acted on without debate or consideration of
amendments. The three critics were not identified.
   Due to the two-week Easter recess, the Senate will not be back in
session for the rest of the month. Currently, some 6,000 to 7,000
AIDS victims are receiving AZT under the program.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Child Safety Seats Recalled</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1.5 million Fisher-Price car safety
seats for children are being recalled by the manufacturer because
they do not meet federal flammability standards.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said on Friday
that the company's own tests prompted the recall of the seats, which
are Models 9100 and 9101 manufactured from 1985 to 1989.
   The company discovered the foam seat pad used in the two models
burns faster than federal standards permit, NHTSA said. Since the
pad cover does meet standards, motorists should continue to use the
seats until they get replacement pads, and should not return them to
stores, the agency said.
   Owners of the affected seats may call a Fisher-Price hotline,
800-334-5439, for instructions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Senate Confirms Eagleburger for State Department Post</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has confirmed President Bush's
selection of Lawrence Eagleburger for deputy secretary of state.
   Bush's nomination of Eagleburger for the No. 2 post at the State
Department was approved by voice vote on Friday shortly after the
senators confirmed Dick Cheney for secretary of defense.
   The choice of Eagleburger had been approved a day earlier by the
Foreign Relations Committee, 19-0. That tally even included the vote
of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who spent two days questioning the
nominee's business relations with former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Honeybee Quarantine Imposed to Combat Mite</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is imposing a
federal quarantine affecting 19 states and other areas to help stop
the spread of tiny parasitic mites that threaten the honeybee
industry.
   Officials said the proposed quarantine would also be effective in
the District of Columbia and 15 U.S. territories or other
possessions known or believed to be infested with the Varroa mite.
   ``We are proposing to quarantine all `states' where Varroa mites
are known to occur,'' Al Strating, acting administrator of the
department's Animal and Health Inspection Service, said Friday.
   States listed in the proposal, which was announced on Thursday,
include: Alaska, California, Colorado, Florida, Georgia, Illinois,
Indiana, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Nebraska, New Hampshire, New
York, North Dakota, Ohio, Pennsylvania, South Dakota, Wisconsin and
Wyoming.
   Other areas include: American Samoa, Baker Island, Guam, Howland
Island, Jarvis Island, Johnston Atoll, Kingman Reef, Midway Islands,
Navassa Island, Northern Mariana Islands, Palmyra Atoll, Puerto
Rico, Republic of Palau, U.S. Virgin Islands and Wake Island.
</TEXT>
