<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Flight103-Families     03-18 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103-Families,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families of Flight 103 Victims Demand Federal Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Flight 103, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of five people killed when
a bomb exploded aboard a Pan Am flight over Scotland are demanding
that the U.S. government investigate the bombing.
   ``There is an enormous amount of anger and outrage at the way
we've been treated by this country's government,'' said Barbara
Primeau of Greenwich, N.Y., mother of 20-year-old twins, Jason and
Eric Coker, who were among the 270 people killed in the Dec. 21
crash of Flight 103 in Lockerbie, Scotland.
   Ms. Primeau joined two families of victims from upstate New York
and another family from North Adams at a news conference on Friday.
   The petition drive was launched in this northwest Massachusetts
city because residents have shown concern at the slow progress of
the crash investigation, the families said.
   ``Terrorism and tragedy such as this have never touched this
community before,'' said Mayor John Barrett III, the first to sign
the petition.
   The drive was organized by Joyce Wrend, who was among the 1,000
mourners at the church service for Wendy Lincoln, a Syracuse
University student on her way home from London for Christmas when
the plane blew up.
   ``I'd like to see an outcry from the people so loud that the
government can't forget this,'' said Charles Lincoln in his first
statement since the death of his 23-year-old daughter.
   The petitions will be distributed throughout the Northeast.
Organizers said they hope to get 20,000 signatures by the time they
stage a vigil outside the White House on April 3.
   Ms. Primeau and other family members said they suspect the State
Department knew about the bomb threats but that it remained on the
sidelines before and after the crash.
   ``We're not an investigatory agency,'' Francis Jones, spokeswoman
for the State Department's Office of Consular Affairs in Washington,
said Friday. ``British authorities are investigating the crash and
the FBI is assisting them.''
   ``The investigation is a very lengthy, complicated process. And
it's frustrating, which is very difficult for the families. It's
understandable,'' she added. ``I wish there was something we could
do to make things come together more quickly.''
   Ms. Primeau said the anger of the families was heightened Friday
by a British newspaper report that authorities knew who had bombed
the flight. The report from the Times of London, dismissed by
investigators, has increased their suspicion that the U.S.
government is withholding information about the bombing, she said.
   Pan Am confirmed it had been warned by the West German government
Nov. 10 about the kind of radio-cassette player bomb involved.
   Politicians of the opposition Labor Party in London accused
Transport Secretary Paul Channon with bungling a warning dated two
days before the disaster but not mailed until several days later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
