<FIRST>r a PM-LongDay'sJourney     03-18 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Long Day's Journey,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yale Press Sells Millionth Copy of Its O'Neill Bestseller</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yale University Press has sold its
one-millionth copy of its all-time bestseller, Eugene O'Neill's
``Long Day's Journey Into Night,'' the publisher announced.
   Written in 1940, O'Neill's masterpiece was first performed on
Broadway and published by Yale in 1956, three years after the
playwright's death. It was O'Neill's fourth play to win a Pulitzer
Prize.
   The first paperback version of the work appeared in 1962.
   Sale of the millionth copy of the play, which happened last
month, came shortly after the conclusion of the 1988 centennial
celebration of O'Neill's birth.
   This fall, Yale University Press will publish a corrected version
of the play restoring previously missing lines of dialogue and stage
direction.
   Recent scholarship on the play uncovered several errors of
omission that occurred when the playwright's wife, Carlotta O'Neill,
retyped a heavily edited version of his manuscript.
   The changes in the 61st reprinting are ``meaningful, if not
plentiful,'' said Martha Schutz, a Yale press publicist.
</TEXT>
