<FIRST>r a PM-StPatrick'sDay     03-18 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-St Patrick's Day,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Honor Patron Saint With Parades, Celebrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 2 million people cheered the first woman grand marshal of
the St. Patrick's Day parade in New York City, while in Connecticut
the ``Ladies of the Knights'' protested their exclusion from an
all-male affair.
   The wearin' of the green was prevalent throughout the country as
the Chicago River, the Empire State Building and the palms,
fountains and grits in Savannah, Ga., all shone with the color of
the day.
   The celebrations in honor of Ireland's patron saint continued
today, with parades in Los Angeles and Syracuse, N.Y.
   ``We've got to stop meeting like this,'' Dorothy Hayden Cudahy
told New York City Mayor Edward I. Koch as she kissed him before
taking the historic first step that kicked off the nation's oldest
and largest parade.
   ``I'm the grand marshal and I'm walking on air,'' said Mrs.
Cudahy, 66. She was followed by regiments of police and firefighters
in tam-o'-shanters and marching bands in busbies playing bagpipes,
fifes and drums.
   In New Haven, Conn., four members of the National Organization
for Women staged a satirical protest outside the annual all-male
dinner held by the Knights of St. Patrick.
   Wearing horn-rimmed glasses and outdated clothes, the women waved
handkerchiefs and yelled ``Oh Boys, Boys'' in mock high-pitched
voices as they acted as a tongue-in-cheek welcoming committee for
the Knights, who said the traditional event was just an evening of
camaraderie.
   An estimated 400,000 people lined the downtown Chicago parade
route in a light rain that began shortly after the march began.
Forty thousand marchers and more than 200 floats and marching units
moved down Dearborn Street.
   ``I say I'm Irish,'' said Daniel McQuinn, 25, of Chicago, whose
parents came from Ireland. ``If a cat had a kitten in an oven, would
you call them biscuits? I was born here, but I still say I'm Irish.''
   In Savannah, police estimated 300,000 people watched 265 units
participating in the nation's second-largest St. Patrick's
celebration. The city's 165th parade also honors Irish immigrants
who entered the United States through the East Coast port.
   Los Angeles' Irish had a choice today of two parades: the sixth
annual downtown St. Patrick's Day Parade or the fourth annual St.
Patrick's Day Parade in Hollywood.
   Boston delays its official wearing of the green until Sunday.
Other cities saving their St. Patrick's Day observances until Sunday
included Bayonne and Newark, N.J.; and Buffalo, N.Y.
   At a Mass in St. Patrick's Cathedral that preceded the New York
parade, Cardinal John O'Connor preached a politically charged sermon
chiding the United States for a lack of concern ``with the problems
of Northern Ireland because we believe the Irish love to fight, that
they're a violent people.'' He added the belief the Irish desire
violence was a fallacy in need of correction.
   In Washington, Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan and a bipartisan group of
senators and congressmen issued their ``ninth annual friends of
Ireland'' statement calling for peace, justice, fair employment and
an end to discrimination in Northern Ireland.
   President Bush, sporting a green tie, met in the White House with
Irish Prime Minister Charles Haughey and called on Americans in a
St. Patrick's Day statement to support ``all those who seek justice
and peaceful settlements to disputes in Northern Ireland.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0413EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-RebelTown     03-18 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Rebel Town,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Returned Refugees Shun Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Editor's Note _ An Associated Press correspondent was permitted
to spend several days this week in rebel-controlled territory in El
Salvador. Here is his report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MARTA, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   None of the voting-age residents
in this village of 2,500 plans to cast a ballot in Sunday's
presidential election.
   ``No one here believes in this election,'' said Rodrigo Lainez, a
local leader of this town, which was repopulated in 1987 after being
abandoned for seven years.
   ``This election is to prolong the war,'' said a man who
identified himself only as Victor. His comment echoed a refrain
broadcast daily on two clandestine guerrilla radio stations of the
leftist Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.
   No love is lost between Santa Marta and the U.S.-backed
government of President Jose Napoleon Duarte. His administration and
its army consider the town, like others revived by people who
returned from refugee camps in Honduras, as hostile territory.
   Santa Marta's sympathies clearly lie with the FMLN, the rebel
army waging a nine-year war against the government. The rebels have
called for an election boycott to prove that a political solution is
impossible without their participation.
   Every day from 6 a.m. to 8 a.m., battery-powered radios in Santa
Marta are tuned to Radio Farabundo Marti and Radio Venceremos. Like
many rural communities in El Salvador, this one lacks electricity.
   Women grind corn or pat tortillas as men drink coffee before
heading to the fields. On one morning this week, all listened to a
radio account of overnight attacks on ``the puppet army'' and
admonishments that every Salvadoran do his part to prepare for
insurrection.
   Guerrillas wander through this town in north central El Salvador.
They are greeted with smiles and offered cool melon juice.
   Government soldiers, on their rare appearances, are shunned.
   ``The soldiers three times set fire to the cornfield around
here,'' said Lainez. ``The last time they came through, a few went
up to people and told them, `Just wait until Arena is in power.
We'll be back with a bomb for every house.'''
   Alfredo Cristiani of the rightist Republican Nationalist
Alliance, or Arena, is expected to win Sunday's election. In its
campaign, Arena has taken a hard line on the war, threatening a
military solution.
   Col. Jose Herrarte, the provincial military commander, said in an
interview that he hopes to improve relations with Santa Marta
through more personal contact. But he acknowledges the difficulties.
   ``The subversives count on them for supplies, recruitment and
rest,'' he said. ``They portray us only as murderers, violators of
human rights, ogres.''
   An estimated 20,000 Salvadorans _ mostly from Chalatenango,
Cabanas and Morazan provinces _ were driven from their homes by the
war, aerial bombardments and repression in the early 1980s. Since
October 1987, about 6,500 have returned to rebuild their lives.
   ``When we came back, this was just woods and brush,'' said
Lainez. ``Every house had been burned, and the fields were
overgrown.''
   He said most residents never lost hope of going home. ``Our
umbilical cords are buried here,'' he said, using a Salvadoran
expression conveying the importance of one's roots.
   For their part, the guerrillas refer to the local residents as
``the heroic resettlers of Santa Marta.''
   ``They came back to confront the army without weapons,'' said a
local guerrilla commander who identified himself only as Antolin.
   During its first year of reconstruction, the town depended on
charity from the International Red Cross, the United Nations and
church groups. But last year yielded a good harvest, and the village
is nearly self-sufficient in corn and beans, the daily staples.
   A walk through the settlement showed residents building latrines,
making adobe blocks, working on a chicken coop and pounding dried
stalks of millet to separate the kernels from the chaff. Many are
enlarging their homes of adobe, mud-and-wattle and corrugated metal
roofs.
   The social arrangement is largely cooperative, with familes
permitted small private plots to augment their communal ration.
   ``Because of the war, there are lots of widows and orphans
here,'' said Lainez. ``If we weren't a cooperative, those people
would die.''
   He said soldiers in the provincial capital of Sensuntepeque often
stop trucks headed for Santa Marta loaded with donated food,
clothing or construction materials.
   ``They think everything we bring up here is for the guerrillas.
But we barely have enough for ourselves and aren't in a position to
give things away,'' Lainez said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
