<DOCNO> AP890318-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia-Peace     03-18 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Peace,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government, Guerrillas To Begin Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and the country's most
feared guerrilla group have signed an accord to begin talks toward
ending nearly two decades of bloody insurgency.
   President Virgilio Barco in a nationwide television address
Friday night asked the other Colombian rebel groups to follow suit.
   ``I urge all guerrillas to integrate themselves in civilian life.
The road is always open,'' Barco said.
   An estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas operate in Colombia. They
are blamed for more than 2,000 deaths and nearly 500 kidnappings in
1988 alone.
   The accord was signed Friday in the mountain town of Santo
Domingo, 180 miles south of Bogota, by the minister of interior,
Raul Orejuela Bueno, and Carlos Pizarro, commander of the M-19, or
the April 19 Movement.
   The April 19 Movement takes its name from a 1970 presidential
election that the guerrillas say was fraudulent.
   Once the nation's most notorious group, M-19's bloodiest
operation was seizing the Supreme Court building in Bogota in 1985.
The army retook the building, but 11 Supreme Court justices and 85
other people were killed.
   A joint declaration said four meetings that led to the accord
were held in Colombia and Mexico after the leftist guerrillas
declared a unilateral cease-fire eight months ago.
   The declaration said both sides agreed on talks beginning April 1
that would ``lead to full democracy'' and reintegrate the insurgents
into society.
   The talks are to finish before legislative elections set for
March 1990, in which M-19 probably will participate as a legal
political party, officials said.
   The agreement did not say when the guerrillas would have to give
up their arms.
   Barco said the accord ``opens a time of hope for the fate of the
country,'' but he said there large obstacles to overcome before
attaining peace.
   He signaled that the government is ready to begin talks with the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, a communist rebel group that
declared a unilateral cease-fire Feb. 28 in an effort to join the
peace process.
   However, Barco said the cease-fire must hold for a certain period
of time to determine if the FARC has ``a genuine spirit of
reconciliation.''
   The joint declaration also said the guerrillas will no longer
operate underground and will base themselves in Santo Domingo, where
they receive state protection and will not be subject to harassment
by the army.
   During the signing ceremony, Orejuela said all sides must stay
vigilant because ``there are people interested in seeing that a
process like this one fails.''
   The declaration said 13 guerrilla delegates who had no criminal
record participated in the talks and had government protection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-GreatWall     03-18 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Great Wall,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans Canceled For Cable Car Up China's Great Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of Beijing has halted plans to build a
cable car up the side of the Great Wall, yielding to
preservationists who said it would desecrate China's most famous
landmark, official newspapers said today.
   The battle over the cable car had been fought for two years, with
the main support coming from the Chinese builder and an army unit
stationed near the Great Wall that was to supply engineers for the
project.
   The China Daily newspaper said Beijing Mayor Chen Xitong listened
to both sides at a meeting this month before deciding. He convened
the meeting after opponents publicly accused his office of pushing
the project through in violation of a 1988 law protecting cultural
relics.
   The cable car was to have been built at Badaling, about 43 miles
north of Beijing, where for a few dollars tourists can walk along a
small restored section of the Great Wall.
   Under the cultural relics law, no construction is allowed within
600 feet of the wall at Badaling.
   The Great Wall, a dramatic symbol of China's historic fear of
foreign contact, actually began as a series of short walls built by
independent kingdoms and principalities to keep out invaders.
Efforts to build one unified wall began about 200 B.C. under China's
first emperor, Qin Shi Huangdi.
   The completed wall finally stretched 3,700 miles from the desert
plains of north-central China to the sea. Large portions are now in
ruins.
   The Badaling Tourism Service Co. and Golden Glory International
Co. of Hong Kong signed a contract to build the cable car a year
before the cultural relics law was passed. Golden Glory agreed to
invest $5 million in the project, with a $1.5 million guarantee if
it was canceled, the China Daily said.
   China Youth News said more than 20 architects and officials from
the Beijing and national cultural relics bureaus led the battle
against the cable car. They even took the rare step of writing a
letter to Premier Li Peng.
   Several engineers concluded after a study that the project would
lose money.
   Officials who backed the cable car said it would ease crowding on
the wall and thereby prevent damage. Thousands of people visit the
wall each day during the tourism season, from about April to October.
   Tourists currently reach the top via one central set of stairs,
then can walk along the wall in both directions for several hundred
feet. The wall is about 30 feet high at Badaling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0031 </DOCNO>
