<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-18 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow, Thunderstorms Touch Various Areas Of U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow and thunderstorms touched various areas of the nation today
as some regions assessed damage from hail and high winds.
   Snow fell in northern Vermont and northern New York this morning,
as well as parts of Michigan, Wisconsin, Illinois, Iowa, Minnesota,
South Dakota, Nebraska and Montana.
   Showers and thunderstorms were reported in northeast Oklahoma,
northwest Arkansas, southern Missouri, southern Illinois, northern
Indiana and northern Ohio.
   Freezing rain fell across western New York.
   On Friday, afternoon and evening thunderstorms extended from near
Tulsa, Okla., to near Fort Smith, Ark., and in parts of Missouri,
Illinois and Indiana.
   The National Weather Service received countless reports of small
hail and more than two dozen reports of hail ranging in size from
three-quarters of an inch in diameter to the size of baseballs.
Largest hail fell near Hulbert, Okla.
   There were nearly a dozen reports of damage from thunderstorm
wind gusts, but no injuries were reported from the storms.
   Snowfall diminished in Minnesota and western Wisconsin during the
evening, after leaving up to 3 inches of snow in northern
Minneapolis-St. Paul and about 8 inches south of the metropolitan
area. Other snowfall totals in Minnesota included about 9 inches at
Farmington and 6 inches at Chaska.
   Snowfall totals by midnight in lower Michigan included 11 inches
at Hart; 10 inches at Big Rapids and Cadillac; 9 inches at Gaylord
and Houghton Lake; and 8 at Manistee, Mount Pleasant, Ludington and
Clare,
   The high Friday was 95 degrees at Childress, Texas.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from the lower Mississippi Valley across the Tennessee Valley and
the Ohio Valley to the middle Atlantic Coast and southern New
England, with thunderstorms most numerous over the Carolinas and
Virginia; snow from southern parts of the upper Great Lakes to
northern New England; rain continuing across the Pacific Northwest,
northern California and northern Nevada; and snow in the northern
Rockies.
   Predicted highs: teens and 20s from the northern Plains across
the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes, and northern
Maine; 30s and 40s from the northern Rockies across much of the
central Plains, the middle Mississippi Valley and northern parts of
the Ohio Valley to northern New England; 70s and 80s in Southern
California, the southern Plains, the southern Rockies, most of
Texas, the Gulf Coast of Mexico states, the southern Appalachians to
Florida, and the southern Atlantic Coast.
   The rest of the nation should reach the 50s and 60s.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8 degrees
below zero at Warroad, Minn., to 74 degrees at Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 60 fair; Boston 39 cloudy; Buffalo 31 freezing
rain; Charleston, S.C. 58 foggy; Cincinnati 66 rain; Cleveland 33
foggy; Detroit 32 rain; Miami 73 fair; New York 47 foggy;
Philadelphia 53 fair; Pittsburgh 67 windy; Portland, Maine 32
cloudy; Washington 57 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 13 cloudy; Chicago 28 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 67 fair; Denver 33 partly cloudy; Des Moines 14 snow;
Indianapolis 44 windy; Kansas City 22 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 9
fair; Nashville 69 partly cloudy; New Orleans 65 foggy; St. Louis 34
foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 50 fair; Anchorage 22 fair; Las Vegas 54
cloudy; Los Angeles 54 fair; Phoenix 68 fair; Salt Lake City 32
cloudy; San Diego 56 fair; San Francisco 55 cloudy; Seattle 46
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 21 snow; Toronto 23 freezing rain.
</TEXT>
