<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Chile     03-18 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Chile,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Lifts Sanctions On Chilean Grapes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fruit-Cyanide, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan today lifted a four-day suspension on
importing Chilean grapes after Chile pledged to step up safety
precautions as a result of a cyanide scare, Japanese officials said.
   The Japanese government ordered the suspension Tuesday after
traces of cyanide were discovered Monday in two Chilean grapes
shipped to Philadelphia. The discovery followed anonymous threats to
the Japanese and U.S. embassies in Santiago that Chilean fruit would
be poisoned.
   The Chile government has reassured Tokyo it will step up safety
precautions to guarantee that grape shipments are safe, leading
Japan to lift its ban on imports, said Health and Welfare Ministry
official Katsumi Itoi.
   The decision comes on the heels of an announcement Friday by
Washington that Chilean fruit exports were once again welcome in the
United States.
   It also comes after the detention Thursday in southern Chile by
naval authorities of five Japanese fishing boats ``for safety
inspection.''
   Chilean navy commander Adm. Jose Merino initially said the ships
were being held until Japan lifted its ban.
   But Friday in a telephone interview, Chilean navy Lt. Jose Araya
said, ``The boats are retained and being subject to a mandatory
thorough inspection.
   ``This is necessary for the safety of all people on board those
vessels. Once inspectors are satisfied with the safety standards of
the boats, they will let them sail off.''
   Itoi, asked if the decision to lift Japan's ban on Chilean grapes
was diplomatically motivated, said: ``The health of the Japanese
people is our primary concern.''
   There was no immediate word today from Chile on Japan's lifting
of the ban.
   Japan has imported 1,775 tons of grapes from Chile so far this
year, representing about 20 percent of Japan's total imported grapes
for the period, according to government figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
