<FIRST>r a PM-MedicaidAbortion     03-18 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicaid Abortion,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU Plans Appeal Of Judge's Ruling To Uphold Ban On Medicaid Abortions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for a 15-year-old allegedly impregnated
in a gang rape plan to appeal a court ruling upholding a law that
bans Medicaid funding for abortions.
   Circuit Judge John H. Hausner said in a 26-page opinion issued
Friday that there are no constitutional provisions entitling the
teen-ager to state money for an abortion.
   An appeal will be filed Monday with the state Court of Appeals,
said Elizabeth Gleicher, an attorney for the American Civil
Liberties Union, which brought the lawsuit on the girl's behalf.
   The ACLU contends the Medicaid ban is unconstitutional because it
discriminates against poor women.
   The lawsuit is the first challenge of the state's Medicaid-funded
abortion ban, which took effect Dec. 12 after voters approved it in
the Nov. 8 general election.
   The ACLU also will file a motion Monday asking the state Supreme
Court to hear the case immediately, bypassing the appellate court,
Gleicher said. The appeals process will continue even if the
teen-ager has an abortion, she added.
   ``Obviously we're unhappy and displeased with the judge's
decision,'' Gleicher said. ``But we always knew from the very start
that this case would have to be decided in the state Supreme Court.''
   Lawyers for the state and groups opposed to abortion were pleased
with the ruling.
   ``The will of the people has been vindicated. The ACLU's attempt
to impose its will on the will of the people has been rejected,''
said John Curcio, an attorney for Right to Life of Michigan.
   According to the ACLU, the teen, identified only as ``Jane Doe,''
became pregnant during a Jan. 15 rape and can't afford abortion
costs of between $250 and $1,000.
   ``If Jane Doe wants an abortion it cannot be funded by the state
Medicaid program but that does not mean that an abortion is not
available,'' Hausner said.
   Hausner cited the testimony of doctors who said they sometimes
perform abortions for free.
   Two of the teen-ager's alleged attackers, Aaron Wallace, 20, and
Edward Costnar, 17, both of Detroit, face trial on first-degree
criminal sexual assault charges on April 7.
</TEXT>
