<FIRST>r i PM-Mozambique-Expulsion     03-18 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mozambique-Expulsion,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portuguese Diplomat Ordered To Leave Maputo As Dispute Deepens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today ordered a
Portuguese diplomat to leave the country within four days,
apparently in retaliation for Portugal's expulsion of a Mozambican
diplomat suspected of involvement in an assassination.
   Mozambique's Foreign Ministry said Jose da Silva Pereira,
commercial consul at the Portuguese Embassy in Maputo, has been
declared persona non grata and must leave by midnight Tuesday.
   The ministry accused the consul of engaging in unspecified
activities ``incompatible with his diplomatic status.'' The ministry
statement did not mention Portugal's expulsion Friday of Rafael
Custodio Marques, third secretary at the Mozambican Embassy in
Lisbon.
   Portugal accused Marques of involvement in the killing of former
Mozambican rebel leader Evo Fernandes. The expulsion order was
issued after Mozambique refused to waive Marques' diplomatic
immunity so he could be questioned about the case.
   The dispute has strained relations between Portugal and its
former colony at a time when links between them were growing.
   Portuguese newspapers have said a man held in connection with the
murder of Fernandes, former general-secretary of the Mozambican
National Resistance rebels, accused Marques of helping plan the
killing.
   According to the reports, Alexandre Chagas confessed to the
murder and said he was acting for the Mozambican government.
   Mozambique denies all involvement in Fernandes' death, claiming
he was killed as a result of infighting among the rebels.
   Portuguese police found Fernandes' body last April on a hillside
near Lisbon. He had been shot in the head and chest.
   Chagas and Joaquim Messias were arrested in Morocco and
extradited to Portugal to face charges in connection with the
killing.
   Fernandes, a Portuguese citizen, was a founder member of the
rebel movement and was its general secretary from 1983-1986.
   He was demoted to head of the rebels' research department but
observers said he remained an influential figure within the
organization.
   The rebels have waged a hit-and-run insurgency against
Mozambique's Marxist-oriented government since 1977, two years after
independence. Portugal does not support the the rebels, but allows
them to maintain an office in Lisbon.
</TEXT>
