<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Korea     03-18 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Accuses United States of Mock Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist North Korea today accused the
United States of staging simulated nuclear attacks with B-52 bombers
on the Korean peninsula and demanded a halt to U.S.-South Korean
military exercises.
   U.S. officials rejected the North Korean charge. American forces
based in South Korea are believed to have nuclear weapons, though
Washington refuses to address the issue.
   North Korean officials said the U.S. Air Force was using up to
nine B-52 bombers from bases in Guam to stage daily nuclear attack
exercises over parts of South Korea that resemble targets in the
North. The officials said the exercise was preparation for a nuclear
attack on the North.
   Also today, radical students with firebombs battled riot police
in Seoul and Kwangju after rallies to demand withdrawal of U.S.
forces from South Korea. Riot police fired tear gas to drive back
about 400 protesters at Dongguk University in Seoul and about 800
protesters at Chonnam University in Kwangju.
   ``Yankee go home!'' and ``Withdraw U.S. forces!'' protesters
shouted.
   About 200,000 U.S. and South Korean troops are taking part in the
annual exercises, which began Tuesday and end next week. The ``Team
Spirit'' exercises practice bringing in U.S. reinforcements in the
event of a North Korean attack.
   About 42,000 American soldiers are normally stationed in South
Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   North Korean delegates to the Military Armistice Commission
meeting at the border site of Panmunjom demanded U.S. and South
Korean forces immediately halt the annual exercises. The North once
again said the exercises are a grave threat to peace on the divided
peninsula and a barrier to peace talks.
   ``You should desist from attempting to justify your aggressive
acts and discontinue at once the criminal war exercise ... blocking
the way to detente and dialogue by leading the situation to the
brink of war,'' said North Korean Maj. Gen. Choe Ui Ung.
   The Armistice Commission polices the armistice that ended the
Korean War in 1953.
   U.S. Navy Rear Admiral Larry Vogt, head of the U.N. Command, and
other U.S. officials said no nuclear attacks were being practiced.
Vogt dismissed the North Korean charges as meaningless propaganda.
   The U.N. Command represents the 16 nations that sent troops to
aid capitalist South Korea against the 1950 North Korean invasion.
   Vogt charged North Korea was building up its military as part of
possible plans to attack South Korea. A North Korean attack launched
the Korean war in 1950.
   ``Your side's continued military buildup, forward deployment of
forces and secret military maneuvers _ all directed against the
Republic of (South) Korea _cause serious concern that your side may
be preparing for another act of aggression,'' Vogt said.
   Vogt repeated the U.S. position that the ``Team Spirit''
exercises are purely defensive.
   North Korea in the past has denounced the maneuvers and charged
they are part of preparations for a U.S. attack. But the exercises
this year stalled North-South talks on easing tensions. North Korea
said last month that progress in government talks was impossible if
the South went ahead with the exercises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
