<FIRST>r a PM-ShootingTrek     03-18 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shooting Trek,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Carolina Family Tells Of Abduction By Man Fleeing Shooting
Scene</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family in New York for a funeral was
abducted by a man fleeing the scene of his wife's shooting and
forced to drive him in their car while he loaded a pistol and licked
the tip of each bullet.
   ``I thought he was going to kill us for sure,'' said Bobby Gee,
54, of Rocky Mount, N.C. ``We started to pray out loud as soon as he
got into the car. He told us to shut up.''
   The family was released uninjured after a harrowing two-hour
odyssey on the side of a highway on New York's Long Island and the
man turned himself in to Paterson police hours later.
   Victor Otero, 39, turned himself in Friday afternoon, and was
arrested on charges of attempted murder, kidnapping, armed robbery
and unlawful possession of a weapon, Police Sgt. Craig Perrone said.
Otero was being held pending arraignment this morning.
   Police said Otero was wanted for the Thursday night shooting of
his estranged wife, 34-year-old Evelyn Diaz Otero. She was in
critical condition late Friday at St. Joseph's Medical Center, said
a nursing supervisor.
   The shooting began an interstate trek across the Hudson River and
a manhunt that involved police from Paterson, New York City and
Nassau County.
   Otero shot his wife several times about 10:15 p.m. Thursday in
this northern New Jersey city and fled in his own car only to get
into an accident a few blocks away, police said.
   Witnesses told police Otero pulled a revolver and ordered Nelson
Vazquez of Paterson to drive him to New York City. Vazquez dropped
Otero off near the New York end of the Lincoln Tunnel, police said.
   Otero then spotted Mrs. Gee and her family at a pay phone calling
a cousin for directions, The New York Times reported in today's
editions.
   The family _ Mrs. Gee's husband, Allious, 74; her grandson
Cedrick, 4, and her children from a previous marriage, Joel Hardy,
29, an Army staff sergeant stationed in Germany, and Barbi Hardy, 18
_ had left North Carolina early Thursday afternoon for the funeral
of Mrs. Gee's uncle in New York City.
   The gunman forced the family to drive him to Long Island.
   For a while, the Times said, Otero had the pistol aimed at Joel
Hardy's head as Hardy tried to find a way to Long Island. Part of
the time, he methodically loaded the gun and licked the tip of each
bullet before shoving it into the pistol chamber, the Times quoted
Barbi Hardy as saying.
   ``Now, I can shoot you all,'' Miss Hardy recalled the gunman
saying. ``One mistake and I'll shoot the boy in the head.''
   The gunman forced the family out of the car on the Long Island
Expressway, police said. Perrone said there were no reports of
injuries to the family or Vazquez.
   Otero then fled on foot. He contacted his relatives while on the
run and was talked into giving himself up, Perrone said.
</TEXT>
