<HEAD>Clark Taking Sabbatical, Considering Position With Bush Administration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bat-wielding principal portrayed in the
movie ``Lean on Me'' is taking a leave of absence and considering a
post in the Bush administration.
   Eastside High School Principal Joe Clark said Friday that he is
in preliminary negotiations with drug czar William Bennett
concerning a job in Washington.
   ``Regardless of the outcome, I have decided to take a sabbatical
beginning in September 1989,'' Clark said in a statement.
   Clark also said his future plans include promoting his book,
``Laying Down The Law,'' writing a second book, developing
educational videos and increasing his lecture schedule.
   Clark was recently suspended for five days from Eastside over a
school assembly last month featuring a sequined dancer who stripped
her male partners down to G-strings. He said he was out of town
promoting ``Lean On Me'' on the day of the assembly and never
expected the dance group to perform as it did.
   Clark did not return telephone messages late Friday.
