<FIRST>u i PM-Flight103 2ndLd-Writethru   03-18 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0454,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Security Measures Imposed After Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with new security measures at
airports. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Adley in...'' TRIMS thereafter to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have issued new security orders to all
major British airports as a result of the December bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103, a Manchester Airport spokesman said today.
   The reported orders came amid criticism by opposition Parliament
members, who say the government mishandled a warning of a terrorist
attack before the disaster, which killed 259 people on board and 11
on the ground in Scotland.
   The Department of Transport refused to confirm any new orders,
saying it would not discuss security arrangements.
   The Manchester Airport spokesman, who in keeping with British
practice refused to be identified, said the orders were received
Friday night. He gave no details because they dealt with security
matters.
   British new reports said the directive is believed to require
that all passengers be ordered to remove electrical and electronic
equipment from suitcases when they check in.
   They would then carry the items as hand luggage to be examined at
boarding gates, the British Broadcasting Corp. and other news
organizations said.
   Investigators have said the bomb that blew up Flight 103 on Dec.
21 over Lockerbie, Scotland, was concealed in a radio-cassette
player. The New York-bound flight originated in Frankfurt, West
Germany, and passengers and luggage changed to a Boeing 747 in
London's Heathrow Airport.
   On Feb. 18, the Department of Transport advised all airlines
using British airports to begin asking travelers if their baggage
contained radios, computers or other electronic equipment and then
to examine the items for explosives.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon was criticized after admitting
this week in the wake of newspaper disclosures that authorities were
warned terrorists might bomb an aircraft with explosives hidden in a
radio-cassette player.
   In New York, Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon confirmed Friday
that the airline had received a warning from the West German
government on Nov. 10 about the kind of radio-cassette bomb that
caused the disaster. Pan Am has also acknowledged receiving a
warning from the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration.
   But it said it received the British warning by mail weeks after
the air disaster. Channon said this week the British warning
contained ``unimportant'' information that supplemented what was in
the earlier warnings.
   A legislator in the governing Conservative Party on Friday
accused ``hysterical Americans'' of a witch hunt, while party
members rallied to fend off opposition charges over the airport
security controversy.
   ``If every government and every airline broadcast every warning
from every source _ crank or terrorist _ international air travel
would grind to a halt,'' the legislator, Robert Adley, said Friday.
``The culprit ... is the person who planted the bomb. It is not the
(British) Secretary of State for Transport.''
   Adley in his statement said ``malicious (opposition) Labor Party
politicians, hysterical Americans and news-hungry media'' had united
in a ``witch hunt aimed at the Conservative government'' and Channon.
   Adley, a senior member in the party of Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, is an officer of the Conservative legislators' committee
on transport.
   Another Tory legislator, David Wilshire, said Friday that some
relatives of victims have been ``blaming the British government,
blaming Heathrow (airport), blaming anybody except the people I
think they ought to be complaining about: namely the American
government and Pan Am.''
   In Massachusetts, however, the parents of five American people
who died aboard the flight opened a petition drive Friday demanding
a U.S. inquiry and accusing Washington of treating them in a shoddy
manner.
   ``There is an enormous amount of anger and outrage at the way
we've been treated by this country's government,'' said Barbara
Primeau of Greenwich, N.Y. She spoke at a news conference in North
Adams, Mass.
   Her 20-year-old twins, Jason and Eric Coker, who were among the
victims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
