<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Amnesty     03-18 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Amnesty,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Criticizes Amnesty Petitions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's official Xinhua News Agency today
condemned recent petitions for the release of political prisoners
and sought to discredit the requests as invitations for foreign
pressure on China.
   The Xinhua commentary was the latest in a series of official
statements seeking to quell a growing clamor by Chinese
intellectuals for an amnesty for prisoners of conscience and greater
freedom of expression.
   China's leading dissident, astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, first
suggested an amnesty in an open letter to senior leader Deng
Xiaoping in January.
   Since then, 118 other intellectuals have signed three similar
letters, and hundreds of Chinese studying in the United States,
Chinese-Americans, Hong Kong Chinese and Taiwanese have signed
petitions of support.
   Several delegates are expected to push the idea at the National
People's Congress, China's legislature, which begins its annual
session Monday.
   The strongly worded Xinhua commentary, with its warning of
``foreign interference,'' appeared to be an effort to head off any
public statement at the congress that could embarrass the government.
   Xinhua accused the letter writers of ``using foreign public
opinion to exercise pressure on the Chinese government,'' although
no foreign government has officially commented on the amnesty drive.
   It noted that several of the letters appealed for the release of
Wei Jingsheng, a former Beijing electrician who was sentenced in
1979 to 15 years in jail for ``counterrevolutionary crimes.''
   Xinhua said Wei's case was raised ``not because he is important
but because his case aroused much discussion in the foreign press
when it became public in 1979.'' The London-based human rights group
Amnesty International has championed Wei.
   ``The Chinese people suffered enough from foreign invasions
before the liberation of the country,'' the commentary said. ``Many
problems and difficulties do exist, but these are China's own
affairs which the Chinese people will overcome by themselves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
