<FIRST>u a PM-MilitaryCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0465 03-18 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0465,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed In Military Cargo Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes from witness, other detail; CORRECTING
location of crash to seven sted five miles north of the base. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cargo plane carrying explosives
crashed after takeoff from Carswell Air Force Base early today,
killing the two people on board and igniting numerous grass fires,
authorities said.
   Air Force Lt. Brad Schudt said the two people killed likely were
civilians because the DC-9 was a private aircraft under contract to
the Air Force. The victims' identities were not immediately
available.
   ``All of the pastures were on fire,'' said Glen Youngblood, a
rancher who lives near the ranch where the plane crashed. ``I could
see the plane's tires and they were on fire. I told my wife it was a
plane crash, then I went to look to see if I could help.''
   He drove through burning pastures in his truck but found no
survivors.
   Pentagon spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Edward Lundquist said the plane was
operated by Evergreen Air, a private contractor based in Oregon. The
plane that crashed was based in Marana, Ariz.
   The plane was en route to Tinker Air Force Base in Oklahoma when
the crash occurred about 2:30 a.m., said Air Force Senior Airman
Mark Webb. A military board will investigate the crash, officials
said.
   He said the cargo included 32 explosive fuses, which weigh a
total of about 11 pounds.
   The plane crashed into a field about seven miles north of the
base, which is about seven miles west of downtown Fort Worth.
   Robert Parkey, an investigator for the Tarrant County Medical
Examiner's Office, said he had been unable to go to the scene
because the area was cordoned off until daylight.
   Youngblood said the wreckage was scattered over five acres.
   ``If it had been in a populated area, there would have been more
lives lost than two,'' he said. ``It would have destroyed a lot of
people and homes.''
   The wreckage was almost unrecognizable in predawn light as an
airplane except for its large landing wheels and its instrument
panels, Youngblood said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
