<DOCNO> AP890318-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Polan`-Solidarity 1stLd-Writephru a0473 03-18 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polan`-Solidarity, 1st Ld-Writephru, a0473,0030</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Gather For Congress Of Banned Trade Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes, details of meeting. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To haunting strains of a newly composed
hymn, Polish farmers gathered with a sense of vindication today for
the first national congress in eight years of their banned union,
Rural Solidarity.
   ``We meet here in a dramatic situation,'' Rural Solidarity
chairman Jozef Slisz said. ``The national economy is destroyed.
People in towns and villages live on the edge of poverty. But this
is our country. We have to save it for ourselves and our children.''
   The congress brought together farmers from every region of the
country, plus foreign guests and a visit from Lech Walesa, chairman
of the allied independent workers' union, Solidarity.
   It took place even before the end of talks between the opposition
and communist authorities, which have yielded agreement in principle
to legalize Solidarity, Rural Solidarity and the Independent
Students' Association.
   All three were banned after martial law was introduced December
1981. On Tuesday, Parliament will consider draft legislation to
legalize them again.
   ``During those eight years, which we spent in prison or in
hiding, we did not forget the ideals of Solidarity. Some of our
colleagues paid with their lives,'' Slisz said.
   ``We can meet again after eight years thanks to Mr. Walesa,
thanks to his persistence and determination. He is the symbol of
Solidarity for cities and villages.'' The hall erupted into chants
of ``Solidarnosc! Solidarnosc!'' when Walesa appeared.
   ``My role has been to lead you to this point, so that you can
meet and decide about your own activities,'' Walesa told them.
   Many farmers had traveled on overnight trains or slept in cars to
be on hand for the opening Mass at a modern church on Warsaw's
northern outskirts.
   Artur Balazs, a member of Rural Solidarity's national council,
said 450 delegates were attending, with 50 invited guests and
advisers.
   They met in a basement hall of the church dominated by a banner
proclaiming the National Congress of Rural Solidarity, 1981-89.
   Slisz said the congress must ensure that Rural Solidarity is
legalized and prepare for national elections of the union in
December.
   The Rev. Jan Bijak told farmers to draw inspiration for their
reborn organization from traditional values that made peasant
farmers the backbone of the nation. In a new hymn composed for the
congress, an altar assistant then sang, ``Mother lead us to your
Son, through our beloved soil.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Salvador-Geograph     03-18 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Salvador-Geograph,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>El Salvador at a Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at El Salvador, a
nation nestled in the soft Pacific curve of Central America, a land
with a history of violence that is named for Jesus:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GEOGRAPHY _ The country covers 8,260 square miles, about the size
of Massachusetts. It is rugged, a land of volcanoes and lakes and
rich soil. It is about 950 miles southwest of Miami, 950 miles
southeast of Brownsville, Texas.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POPULATION _ Its more than 5 million people are mainly Roman
Catholic and mestizo _ people of both Indian and Spanish heritage.
More than 500,000 of its residents have fled its 9-year-old civil
war, most of them to the United States.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ It was conquered in 1525 by the Spanish. It became
independent on Sept. 15, 1821 and joined the Central American
Federation, which later split into the nations that now make up
Central America.
   It was ruled for most of this century by a land-owning oligarchy
in alliance with the military.
   In 1932 a peasant rebellion organized by Farabundo Marti was
crushed by a military regime that killed 30,000 people; the leader
of that rebellion inspired the present guerrillas, the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ECONOMY _ It is mostly agricultural, with coffee the main cash
crop. In the 1960s and 1970s it became a manufacturing center for
the Central American market. Its largest input is U.S. military and
civil aid, which comes to $1.5 million a day.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE WAR _ The conflict began in 1979 when a group of young
officers overthrew then-president Gen. Carlos Humberto Romero. A
junta tried to impose agrarian and social reforms, but dissatisfied
leftists began a rebellion in late 1979.
   The conflict has led to more than 70,000 deaths, most of them
civilian, many of them suspected leftists killed by right-wing death
squads in the early 1980s.
   In 1984, Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian Democrat, became the
first popularly elected president in 50 years. Sunday's election
marks the first time Salvadorans have had a chance to replace an
incumbent civilian government with a different party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Solidarity 1stLd-Writethru a0473 03-18 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Solidarity, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO FIX GARBLE IN SLUG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Farmers Gather For Congress Of Banned Trade Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes, details of meeting. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
