<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO FIX GARBLE TO SLUG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Three Palestinians Killed, 17 Wounded In Gaza Strip Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers killed three Palestinians and
wounded at least 17 today in clashes in the occupied Gaza Strip,
Arab reports said.
   The army command confirmed that several Palestinians were killed
and some wounded in riots in Gaza City, but it could not provide
exact figures.
   Also today, the army and Israel radio said a guerrilla squad
sneaked into Israel from Jordan and ambushed an Israeli army patrol
late Friday, killing a soldier and wounding another before escaping
back across the border.
   An Arab reporter in Gaza City said demonstrations occurred today
after Israeli policemen in jeeps and a gravel-firing machine arrived
in the Sheikh Rajwan neighborhood and glued placards to house walls
calling on the residents to maintain quiet. ``What's the benefit of
a demolished house, a killed son?'' the reporter quoted the placards
as saying. The reporter requested anonymity.
   Palestinians angered by the posters gathered at the local mosque
where loudspeakers called for a ``fight against the army,'' he said.
   Protesters took to the streets, pelting the soldiers with rocks,
he said. Youths erected roadblocks and burned tires in other areas
of Gaza City and the refugee camps of Rafah and Jabaliya, Arab
accounts said.
   On a central Gaza City street, an Arab wearing a shirt in the
colors of the banned Palestinian flag was forced to take it off and
then was beaten by soldiers as a crowd of Palestinians hurled stones
from afar, the reporter said.
   Merchants quickly shut down their stores and transportation came
to a halt. Only army vehicles, ambulances and U.N. cars were seen in
the streets, and thick columns of black smoke rose to the sky.
   ``There are burning tires and barricades everywhere,'' one Arab
witness said. ``It looks just like the beginning of the intefadeh,''
or the Palestinian uprising, with mass demonstrations of its early
months.
   In Sheikh Radjwan, where troops opened fire to quell the riots,
three Palestinians were killed, and at least 10 were wounded,
officials at Gaza's Shifa Hospital said. The army clamped a curfew
on the neighborhood.
   Arab doctors identified the fatalities as Fawsi Mohammed Bahid,
20, and Abdel Nasser Sherif, 16, who were both shot in the chest,
and Majdi Kourani, 19, who was shot in the neck.
   Seven other Palestinians were wounded elsewhere in Gaza City and
the seaside Gaza Strip, said doctors at Shifa and Ahli Arab
hospitals in Gaza City.
   About 200 youths surrounded Shifa Hospital, where the slain Arabs
were brought, and clashed with soldiers, an Arab reporter said.
   The deaths brought to 399 the number of Palestinians killed since
the rebellion began on Dec. 8, 1987, to demand an end to the Israeli
occupation of the Gaza Strip and the West Bank. Seventeen Israelis
have also died.
