<FIRST>u a PM-ShuttleViewing 3rdLd-Writethru a0487 03-18 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Viewing, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0487,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowds Stream Into Shuttle Viewing Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with crowd singing as shuttle lands,
new quotes, other details from scene; Picks up 3rd graf, `Many of ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shuttle Landing, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto EA81</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shuttle watchers who
arrived in a parade of flag-bedecked motorhomes cheered, sang and
cried with pride today as the winged spacecraft Discovery returned
home.
   As the shuttle touched down the flag-waving crowd estimated at
450,000 broke into applause and spontaneously sang the national
anthem.
   Tears streamed from the eyes of some, while others among the
crowd hugged their children. Most snapped pictures furiously,
marveling at the shuttle's steep angle of descent.
   ``I'm just fascinated by it,'' said Bob Dube, 34, of Canyon
Country, Calif.
   Dube was one of hundreds poised for a quick getaway, and was on
the road right after the shuttle landed at 6:36 a.m. to avoid a
massive jam that soon stacked up on the Mojave Desert by the Rogers
Dry Lake public viewing site. Authorities estimated 138,000 vehicles
were on hand.
   ``It's Saturday, if it was a work day I'd hang around a little
longer,'' he said.
   As many as 300 motorists who arrived after roads to the base were
closed simply pulled their vehicles off the highway and drove onto
the desert to watch the landing.
   Several motorists ran into trouble, however, damaging their
vehicles' axles when they drove into large desert potholes.
   Today's crowd of 450,000 was the second-largest to witness a
shuttle landing. The record number was 500,000 for the shuttle
Columbia's July 4, 1982, landing.
   Many of the motor homes jamming the two-lane road leading toward
Rogers Dry Lake, where crowds began gathering earlier this week,
sported huge American flags.
   ``The patriotic spirit here is really something,'' said Ernie
Weiss, 70, of Garden Grove. ``I even bought a new flag for this.''
   Throngs of people, some arriving by motorcycle, others in cars
pulling travel trailers, arrived several days early to claim the
best viewing spots.
   On Friday, the strains of country music blared over loudspeakers
at the makeshift campground as military helicopters buzzed overhead
and skateboarders rattled across the hardened lake bed. Dune buggies
and other off-road vehicles filled the area five miles from the
Edwards Air Force Base landing site with clouds of dust.
   Weiss, who arrived Wednesday, said he was on hand when the
shuttle Atlantis landed last year.
   ``It was really worth it. It raises the hair on your back when
you hear those sonic booms. Teardrops fall and the whole thing,'' he
said.
   Many of the early arrivals were so-called ``snowbirds,'' retired
couples who spend their winters in warm climates.
   ``We winter in the South every year and we just had to see the
shuttle land,'' said 74-year-old Bill Henderson of Sunnyside, Wash.,
who arrived with his wife, Evelyn.
   ``I'm sure we'd see it better on TV, but we just had to be
here,'' he said.
   Pat Tolner, 35, a nurse from Annapolis, Md., witnessed the
shuttle lift off Monday in Florida.
   ``My husband wanted to know what I wanted for Christmas and I
told him I wanted to see the shuttle take off,'' she said. ``I spent
the night in the car and watched it take off, and when I got home I
told him I wanted to see it land. I flew to California Wednesday. I
rented a car and here I am.''
   Mrs. Tolner was quickly adopted by a family in a motorhome and
was celebrating with the rest of the crowd.
   ``Everyone has such a sense of pride and respect,'' she said.
</TEXT>
