<FIRST>r a AM-TenMinutesLate     03-18 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ten Minutes Late,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Jailed After Restroom Stop Made Her 10 Minutes Late For Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was 10 minutes late for a court
appearance because she stopped in a restroom was thrown in jail by a
judge upset by the delay.
   ``It was a complete abuse of discretion, an abuse of the bail
system,'' said attorney Mark Keenheel, representing Karen McCutchen.
   Ms. McCutchen, 23, was late for her preliminary hearing Wednesday
in connection with a robbery but needed to use a restroom, said her
sister, Deborah McCutchen, adding that she went on to the courtroom
to tell officials her sister would be there shortly.
   When Karen McCutchen reached the courtroom, Municipal Court Judge
Edward Mekel demanded to know why she was late, revoked her $10,000
bail, ordered her to jail and raised her bail to $25,000.
   Keenheel said he planned to file a complaint with the Judicial
Inquiry and Review Board. ``It was the most crazy, absurd,
outrageous thing I've ever seen,'' he said.
   A hearing is scheduled for Tuesday for reconsideration of the
increased bail.
   Ms. McCutchen is charged in the robbery of a store whose clerk
picked her photograph out of an array of eight pictures. Keenheel
said he planned to request a lineup during Wednesday's hearing to
see if the clerk could identify Ms. McCutchen in person.
   Deborah McCutchen said the judge accused her sister of staying
out of the courtroom so the clerk wouldn't see her before a lineup
could be arranged.
   Mekel could not be reached for comment Saturday; he was not in
his chambers and his home number is unlisted.
</TEXT>
