<SECOND>AM-BRF--Moonlighting,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC's `Moonlighting' Returns After Hiatus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC is restoring the television series
``Moonlighting'' to its schedule after a four-week hiatus, but the
program is moving to Sunday, according to a network statement.
   The next episode of ``Moonlighting'' is scheduled for broadcast
at 8 p.m. on Sunday, April 2, said the statement issued Friday by
Capital Cities-ABC Television Network Group.
   The comedy was suspended Feb. 28 because last summer's strike by
Hollywood script writers led to a shortage of scripts and left the
argumentative characters, Maddie Hayes and David Addison, without a
word to say, executive producer Jay Daniel said.
   ``The rumor of our death is greatly exaggerated,'' Daniels said
at the time.
   However, ``Moonlighting'' had fallen in the ratings in its fourth
season and was being beaten regularly on Tuesday night's by NBC's
``In the Heat of the Night.''
