<DOCNO> AP890318-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Salvador Bjt   03-18 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Salvador, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Becoming Restive over Salvador Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   El Salvador has been receiving a huge slice of
the U.S. foreign aid program for years but now, as Salvadorans
prepare to elect a new president, many in Congress feel U.S.
taxpayers have not been getting their money's worth.
   The Salvadoran war still rages, having claimed an estimated
70,000 lives, the economy is stagnant and politically-motivated
killings are up, prompting some lawmakers to argue for a major
policy shift regardless of who the next Salvadoran president is.
   The pressure for a new approach is expected to accelerate if, as
expected, the candidate of the rightist ARENA party, Alfredo
Cristiani, wins the election outright on Sunday or the subsequent
runoff.
   His principal opponent is Christian Democrat Fidel Chavez Mena.
   Despite Cristiani's denials, the perception among many who count
in Congress is that ARENA is tied to the death squads _ shadowy
groups who target both real and suspected leftists, sometimes in
cooperation with the military.
   Perception plays a key role in forming opinions on administration
policy. Democrats tend to be outraged by figures that show an
average of 20 political killings a month recently while Republicans
note that such incidents once averaged 800 a month.
   Still, the situation was serious enough to warrant a forceful
appeal last month by Vice President Dan Quayle to the Salvadoran
military ``to work toward the elimination of human rights
violations.''
   The administration also is worried that El Salvador might become
a strategic headache for the United States if the FMLN rebels
triumph. The State Department said Friday that Cuba has been the
source of large quantities of arms shipments to the guerrillas in
recent months.
   The United States has lavished $3.55 billion on El Salvador since
1980 _ the largest program in Latin America _ in a bid to help the
Salvadoran Army defeat the insurrection and to help the country
establish stable democratic rule.
   The strong support for El Salvador reflects in large measure
congressional affection for outgoing President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
whose commitment to democracy is unquestioned but whose legacy,
after almost five years in office, is regarded as mixed at best. Ill
with cancer since last year, Duarte will step down on June 1.
   A congressional report completed recently suggests U.S. policy
has actually made the situation worse in El Salvador.
   Critics, such as Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, a member of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, contend the benefits have been meager
considering the size of the investment.
   ``For the past five years, El Salvador has enjoyed a free ride
with the American taxpayers footing the bill,'' he said Friday. ``By
most standards, U.S. policy has failed the test.''
   Harkin has introduced legislation requiring that half of
Salvador's military aid for 1990 be withheld pending a presidential
report on progress toward prosecution of human rights offenders and
toward ending the war and death squad activity.
   The program for the current year calls for $292.5 in economic aid
and $96.5 in military aid.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on foreign operations, told Secretary of State James A.
Baker III on Wednesday he believes the administration should
emphasize political and diplomatic measures to end Salvador's civil
war.
   ``I think up till now we've tried to implement primarily a
military track and it's failed,'' he said. ``I can't support more
aid with no strings attached without significant changes in our
whole approach to that country.''
   Baker strongly defended the Salvadoran government's approach to
the conflict, pointing out that the army has unilaterally declared a
cease-fire to last through June 1. In addition, five relatively free
elections have been held since 1982 and Duarte has made a number of
efforts to negotiate an end to the war, Baker said.
   Meanwhile, the rebels ``are doing whatever they can to disrupt
the election'' despite their stated desire for peace, Baker said.
   On Friday, State Department spokesman Charles Redman predicted
the rebel tactics will fail.
   ``We condemn FMLN violence and applaud the efforts of ordinary
Salvadorans to establish firmly democratic rule in their troubled
country. The elections on Sunday will be the next step to achieving
that goal,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0058 </DOCNO>
