<FIRST>r a AM-GenerousBartender     03-18 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Generous Bartender,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Happy Hour Special Included Bar's Furniture, Signs And Cash Register</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For one night at the Subs Club bar, everything was
on the house _ even much of the house itself.
   A brash manager, without the owner's permission, apparently gave
away $2,000 worth of liquor, beer and wine, police reported. He also
gave away or sold tables, chairs, glasses, a television set and 15
neon beer signs.
   The cash register also went. The manager apparently pocketed any
money made on the sales, police said.
   ``Apparently their liquor license was expiring and they were
going to close shop,'' police investigator Michael Falls told the
Dallas Times Herald. ``The manager may have just taken advantage of
the situation. He apparently decided to just go ahead and give
everything away.''
   The bar's owner, Jimmy Fields of Garland, discovered the loss
when he arrived about 7:30 p.m. Thursday. Several patrons told him
that the manager told people in the bar at 5 p.m. that they could
have anything they wanted on the house.
   Falls said he tracked down one woman who got in on the windfall
happy hour.
   ``She said he was handing things away right and left and that she
had got a bottle of liquor,'' Falls said.
   Falls said the manager could be arrested and charged with theft
once police make certain that he held no ownership stake in the club.
