<DOCNO> AP890318-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BritishArt     03-18 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-British Art,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Show from Museum in Britain Opens at National Gallery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 400 years ago a young man about London
apparently tried to start what would now be called a punk fashion:
he took to wearing his blonde hair long over his left shoulder but
short on the other side.
   The fashion failed to catch on but the young man, Henry
Wriothesly, Third Earl of Southampton, is remembered anyhow. Many
authorities believe William Shakespeare was writing his sonnets at
the time _ 1594 _ in support of a family effort to make the
20-year-old earl get married and produce an heir.
   Shakespeare wrote two longer poems for him, one with a dedication
evidencing as much friendship as was socially acceptable at that
period between a mere playwright and a nobleman.
   A tiny oval portrait of Southampton, showing the unsuccessful
``lovelock,'' is a feature of a show of ``Treasures from the
Fitzwilliam,'' the museum of Cambridge University in England,
opening Sunday at the National Gallery of Art.
   ``The Fitzwilliam is perhaps Britain's pre-eminent small
museum,'' said J. Carter Brown, director of the National Gallery.
   The painting is by Nicholas Hilliard, the most famous miniaturist
of the period. Only about an inch and a half in height, it was done
on the back of a calfskin playing card. Three hearts can still be
seen on the other side.
   Southampton did get marrieda few years later, after a scandalous
affair with a lady in waiting to Queen Elizabeth. He had been a
favorite of the queen and later she commuted a death sentence
against him for taking part in a conspiracy against her. He died on
a military expedition to the Netherlands in 1624.
   The exhibition includes more than 160 objects from the
Fitzwilliam. They range from a bit of soft-core pornography by the
18th century British satirist William Hogarth to a portrait by Sir
Anthony Van Dyck of Arhcbishop William Laud _ a strict and highly
dignified churchman who helped get King Charles I into a lot of
political trouble 100 years before. Both Laud and the king were
beheaded.
   There are also a little water spaniel in painted porcelain and
assorted coins, drawings, furniture, manuscripts and bronzes.
   The most famous painting is one by Titian that by coincidence
deals with the same subject as Shakespeare's poem to Southampton
with the friendly dedication, ``The Rape of Lucrece.'' The picture
was painted in Italy, about 25 years before Shakespeare wrote the
poem.
   The exhibition will be at the gallery's East Building through
June 18. Then it goes to the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth,
Texas, July 15 to Oct. 8; the National Academy of Design in New
York, Nov. 5 to Jan. 28, 1990; the High Museum of Art in Atlanta,
Georgia, Feb. 20 to May 6, 1990 and the Los Angeles County Museum of
Art, June 21 to Sept. 9, 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FirstDog 2ndLd-Writethru a0474 03-18 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-First Dog, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0474,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Family's Dog Finally Gives Birth</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 9 grafs new to UPDATE with sex of pups, other details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millie, the first dog, was nursing her litter
of six pups today after giving birth at the White House with first
lady Barbara Bush serving as midwife, a spokeswoman for Mrs. Bush
said.
   ``Mom and babies and midwife are doing fine,'' said spokeswoman
Anna Perez, who said the puppies were born over a five-hour period
ending at about 2 a.m. this morning.
   ``It was a wonderfully uneventful birth,'' Ms. Perez said, adding
that the litter contained five females and one male.
   Today the puppies were ``nursing vigorously,'' and Millie had
eaten as well, she said.
   Mrs. Bush took Millie out for a walk twice today.
   Word that Millie was about to deliver came about 9 p.m. Friday as
the Bushes were entertaining a group of guests for a movie, ``New
York Stories,'' in the White House theater following dinner.
   Mrs. Bush slipped quietly out, and, according to Ms. Perez, ``At
the end of the movie, the president announced we had two puppies and
more on the way.''
   Subsequently, ``the president was in on one birth, lending moral
support,'' and he brought Mrs. Bush a folding mattress in the remade
White House beauty salon where the birthing room had been set up.
   Ms. Perez said she was talking on the phone to the first lady
when, ``She said `Here comes George with a bed. Isn't that sweet?'''
   According to Ms. Perez, the sire of the litter was another
springer spaniel, Tug III, owned by a family friend, William Farish,
who also gave them Millie. Tug III lives at Lane's End Farm in
Versailles, Ky.
   ``The puppies are all promised, but for the next four to six
weeks they will live upstairs at the White House,'' the spokeswoman
said.
   Millie's pregnancy had already caused an upheaval in sleeping
arrangements at the highest level of the nation's government.
   Earlier Friday, President Bush disclosed that although the
puppies were born in a whelping box in the beauty parlor, the dog
had been spending her nights in the first family's bedroom.
   Bush said he'd been spending the nights by himself.
   ``The dog refuses to go to the doghouse is the problem,'' Bush
told reporters traveling with him on Air Force One.
   He said the dog adamantly refused to use ``a beautiful pen made
for her to have this blessed event in,'' and insisted on remaining
in the White House master bedroom.
   On Friday, Bush had a bed moved into the beauty parlor for the
first lady, Ms. Perez said. He then went to bed by himself in
another room, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
