<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     03-18 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Erect New Gun Positions In Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian soldiers set up mortars and rocket
launchers on rooftops in the Moslem sector Saturday after the
commander of the Christian army vowed to drive the Syrian army out
of Lebanon.
   Sporadic artillery fire resounded across Beirut on Saturday as
Syrian-backed Druse gunners fired into the state-run Beirut Port and
Christian residential neigborhoods near the city's dividing Green
Line.
   Police said three people were wounded.
   The hostilities violated a cease-fire called Thursday to give
mediators a chance to end fighting that began 10 days ago, killing
49 people and wounding 164, by police count. The truce was to expire
at midnight Saturday.
   The fighting between Moslem and Christian forces began after Gen.
Michel Aoun, the commander of the Christian army, blockaded illegal
ports used by Moslem militias to import supplies.
   The Syrians on Saturday deployed mortars and rocket launchers
atop high-rise apartment buildings in outlying residential districts
of west Beirut and the Shiite Moslem southern slums. They apparently
were preparing for a resumption of the fighting when the truce ends.
   The Syrians maintain a 12,000-strong contingent in west and south
Beirut, part of 40,000 troops stationed in north, east and central
Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   Reliable witnesses, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Syrians also were digging artillery gun pits and foxholes and
erecting new sandbag positions in and around the southern suburbs.
   ``You should not panic,'' one Syrian officer told a visibly
worried resident while the reinforcements were being brought in.
``We're not going to start any fighting. We are here to protect
you.''
   However, hundreds of Shiite residents were seen packing luggage,
beds and mattresses, and leaving the slums on the outskirts of the
capital in cars heading for south Lebanon.
   U.N. officials, who requested anonymity, said more than 8,000
Shiites from Beirut have taken refuge with relatives living in areas
policed by the United Nations peacekeeping forces.
   ``We do not need a guardian who claims he is protecting us ...
while in reality he is killing us, sponging away our wealth and
usurping our sovereignty,'' Aoun said Friday.
   ``Our option is liberation. We shall fight and use every other
means to bring about the Syrian withdrawal,'' said Aoun, 53, a
Maronite Catholic who commands 20,000 mostly Christian troops in
Lebanon's fractured army.
   His remark was criticized by acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a
pro-Syrian official who heads the mainly Moslem cabinet competing
for legitimacy with the Christian military cabinet under Aoun.
   ``You are planting war but you are not going to reap any
liberation,'' said Hoss, a Sunni Moslem. ``The Syrians are here at
the request of legitimate authorities, and their departure can be
decided only by a united cabinet.''
   Their remarks appeared to dim the chances of an agreement to
resolve the latest round of fighting in the 14-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
