<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Collapse     03-18 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Collapse,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Still Missing, Feared Buried Under Rubble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAVIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulldozers and rescue workers searched
through rubble Saturday for two teen-age girls feared buried in the
collapse of a 900-year-old tower.
   Two people were killed and 15 injured when the 255-foot tower
crumbled onto a square in this northern Italian town Friday morning.
   The search for the two girls began after they were reported
missing by their parents. They had failed to show up for work or
return home Friday.
   Throughout the night, bulldozers, firefighters and volunteer
rescue workers dug through the tons of bricks and dirt. Authorities
said the clean-up operation would last through the weekend.
   The tower destroyed a newspaper stand, buried several parked cars
and damaged adjoining shops and parts of the adjacent 501-year-old
cathedral.
   Experts said natural decay of the mortar cementing the bricks
likely caused the collapse. However, heavy August rains that damaged
the church and a recent three-month dry spell that may have weakened
ground around the tower are also being considered as possible causes
for the collapse.
   A magistrate was investigating whether negligence was involved.
   Culture Ministry officials and other departments dealing with
preservation of monuments will meet in Pavia next week to examine
the causes of the collapse and determine measures for preventing
similar incidents.
</TEXT>
