<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-Fun     03-18 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Fun,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Has No Sense Of Humor; But Astronauts Manage a Few Laughs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery's astronauts generally toed
the line on a new NASA edict to cut the comedy, at least for public
viewing, but they showed some flashes of fun in space, mainly in the
battle of wakeup songs.
   When Discovery made the first post-Challenger flight last
September, the five astronauts awoke to Beach Boys music parodies
and clowned for television cameras in bright Hawaiian shirts.
   And even though the December flight of Atlantis was a classified
military mission, word leaked of special wakeup music not
particularly flattering to the Pentagon.
   And both crews videotaped themselves playing in the
weightlessness of orbit, turning somersaults, throwing a football
and feeding each other candy. The tapes were shown at public
gatherings.
   The astronauts' wacky wakeup calls and zany acrobatics got
attention, which upset NASA because it felt the reports made the
flights look like all play and no work.
   ``We've learned that if you crack a joke or show somebody doing
something funny, that's the 10 seconds that gets on the evening
news, and not the two hours worth of work you just showed,''
Discovery commander Michael Coats said in a pre-launch interview.
   So space agency officials told Discovery's crew to cool it when
the cameras or microphones were on.
   ``NASA has no officia sense of humor anymore,'' said Bob
Springer, one of Coats' crewmates. ``So we're somewhat restricted
now on what we can do.''
   Discovery's flight started out strictly following the policy,
with wakeup calls played by Mission Control limited to presentations
like the Marine hymn, for the two crewmen who are Marines.
   But on Day 3, things loosened up.
   The astronauts pre-empted Mission Control by playing their own
wakeup music first _ the theme music from ``Star Trek.''
   They followed that with a tape recorded for them by actor William
Shatner, who gave a brief performance in his character of Capt.
James T. Kirk in the ``Star Trek'' movies and television series.
   ``Discovery, tell Scotty to beam me up,'' replied capsule
communicator David Low in Houston.
   Mission Control then responded with its planned wakeup _ a medley
of school songs from the alma maters of the crew members.
   The next day, the astronauts again were first in the wakeup
battle _ broadcasting a recording of ``Hi Ho, Hi Ho, It's Off To
Work We Go,'' the work song of the seven dwarfs in the animated
movie classic ``Snow White.''
   Mission Control regained the upper hand on the final day,
Saturday, hitting the airwaves first with a raucus recording of the
astronauts' children shouting such things as, ``Get up, dad, get out
of bed and get to work,'' and ``Hi, daddy, this is your darling
daughter telling you to wake up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Anderson-Hometown     03-18 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anderson-Hometown,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Of Hostage's Birth Works For His Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Walter Mears, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LORAIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few residents of this city in northeast Ohio
remember a fair-haired boy named Terry Anderson, who played at his
parents' home while his father worked at a local steel mill.
   But 30 years later, many in the city of 75,000 claim Anderson as
one of their own as they work to free him from captivity in Lebanon.
   ``The city of Lorain has a soft spot in its heart for any Lorain
native,'' said Jack LaVriha, chairman of the Free Terry Anderson
Committee. ``The Andersons are a deep-rooted family here. Terry's
grandfather had a grocery store in south Lorain, and his dad worked
in the steel mills.''
   Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, is the longest-held of nine American hostages in Lebanon. He
began his fifth year in captivity Thursday.
   Anderson's parents are dead, but he still has relatives in
Lorain, an industrial city 30 miles east of Cleveland on Lake Erie.
   The house where Anderson lived until he was 6 or 7 years old has
been torn down, as has the school where he went to first grade, said
Gwen Jones, 78, Anderson's aunt.
   The family left that house when Anderson's father, Glenn, left
the steel mills to work as a truck driver and moved the family to
Batavia, N.Y.
   While LaVriha said he is unaware of any Lorain resident other
than Mrs. Jones who has seen Anderson in the past 30 years, that
hasn't stopped Lorain residents from working on Anderson's behalf.
   Last Christmas, the committee gathered 28,000 Christmas cards for
Anderson that were sent to the State Department with the hope that
the greetings might reach Lebanon. Some of them were published in a
Beirut newspaper.
   Every Oct. 28, residents hold a party in honor of Anderson's
birthday. On March 16 they gather in remembrance of the day he was
captured in 1985, LaVriha said.
   ``The committee has done a lot of work to keep his name alive,''
said a cousin of Anderson's, Leila Arden, 45, who said she hasn't
seen him since he moved from Lorain. ``They've done a lot of work in
making him one of our own.''
   About 500 people wore yellow ribbons, heard music written in
Anderson's honor and released hundreds of balloons Thursday at City
Hall to symbolize their hope that Anderson will be released. More
than 100 of those attending were members of six veterans'
organizations, said another of Anderson's cousins, James Anderson,
vice commander of a local Veterans of Foreign Wars post.
   ``If you are a native of Lorain, whether a veteran or not, we
would have been there,'' he said. ``But Terry's being a Marine and a
veteran of Vietnam makes him kind of special.''
   Lorain native Richard Bacher, who has never met Anderson, wrote a
song called ``We Want You Home Again'' in Anderson's honor last
December. The song, recorded by the Lorain High School Choir,
implores Anderson's captors to ``listen to our plea and send him
home.''
   LaVriha said it has been broadcast by more than 80 U.S. radio
stations and by the Voice of America overseas.
   He said the committee will continue to work to free Anderson.
   ``The main thing is to keep this thing alive. Once we forget the
hostages, they'll be gone,'' LaVriha said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0082 </DOCNO>
