<FIRST>r a AM-People     03-18 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0892</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ruled that a $25 million palimony
lawsuit filed against Jerry Buss, owner of the Los Angeles Lakers,
will go to trial.
   Puppi Buss, also known as Marsha Lee Osborne, claims a monetary
interest in the Lakers; the Lakers' arena, the Great Western Forum;
and Los Angeles Kings, the hockey team once owned by Buss, accrued
during the 16 years or more she spent as Buss' companion,
confidante, homemaker and business partner.
   Superior Court Judge Vernon Foster ruled Friday that ``a triable
issue is created by her declaration that for certain services,''
Buss agreed to share property and to provide her with lifetime
support. The trial was set for July 31.
   Buss' contends that he had never lived with Ms. Buss or promised
to take care of her, that they never owned property jointly, that
they did not travel together regularly and that he did not agree
that she could use his name.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singing cowboy-turned-actor and California
Angels baseball team owner Gene Autry will be the grand marshal of
the 33rd Indianapolis ``500'' Festival Memorial Parade.
   The parade, scheduled for May 27, will have a theme tailor-made
for Autry: ``The American West _ From Frontier to the Future.''
   ``Who represents better the spirit of the American West than Gene
Autry?'' festival President Sid Weedman said Friday.
   After starting out as a singer of Western songs, Autry, now 81,
broke into the movies in 1934, going on to star in a string of
westerns and becoming a top box-office attraction. Later, he was a
television star.
   Among his more than 600 recordings are ``Back in the Saddle
Again,'' ``Tumbling Tumbleweeds,'' and two Christmas hits, ``Rudolph
the Red-nosed Reindeer'' and ``Here Comes Santa Claus.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Bruce Hornsby has reached an
agreement to purchase a 33-acre tract from Colonial Williamsburg, a
foundation dedicated to preserving the colonial capital.
   Hornsby, who is from Williamsburg, and his wife, Kathy, will
build a home on the undeveloped site, which they are purchasing for
$1.2 million, said foundation spokesman Albert O. Louer.
   ``There's no way we could use it for educational purposes,''
Louer said. Archaeological surveys have found some evidence of past
use by humans, but nothing significant, he said.
   The sales contract carries several restrictions on how the wooded
site may be developed, in order to preserve its character, said
Charles Longworth, the foundation's president. The site is a couple
of miles south of the restored village that is a popular tourist
attraction.
   Hornsby, who weaves Virginia imagery into many of his songs, won
a Grammy award in 1987 for best new artist. He and his band, the
Range, are known for the albums ``The Way It Is'' and ``Scenes from
the Southside.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd received Prince Charles on
Saturday as the heir to the British throne consorted with members of
Saudi Arabia's royal family during his private, two-day visit.
   Earlier in the day, the Prince of Wales discussed relations
between Britain and Saudi Arabia and ``all current issues'' at a
meeting with the Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah, the official Saudi
press agency reported.
   The prince, who was scheduled to stay in Saudi Arabia until
Sunday evening, also met with the Saudi foreign minister, Prince
Saud Al-Faisal.
   He visited Kuwait, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates with his
wife, Diana, before arriving in Saudi Arabia for his second visit in
two years. Diana left her husband in Dubai, reportedly returning to
England to attend a friend's wedding.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Clark, whose tough-love brand of
leadership at an inner-city high school made headlines and inspired
a Hollywood movie, is taking a leave of absence from his job and
says he might not return after it's done.
   Clark said Friday that he is in preliminary negotiations with
federal drug czar William Bennett concerning a job in Washington.
   ``Regardless of the outcome, I have decided to take a sabbatical
beginning in September 1989,'' Clark said. His plans include writing
a second book, developing educational videos and increasing his
lecture schedule.
   In an interview with the New York Daily News, he said that ``I
could come back after the year respite, but I would say it's
extremely unlikely.''
   ``My soul is tired and fatigued from fighting an educational
system that's rotten to the core.''
   Clark, who is portrayed in the current hit movie ``Lean on Me,''
has battled with the Paterson school board over his work at Eastside
High School. He was accused of ousting many low-performing students
without following board rules and of creating a safety hazard by
locking doors to keep out drug dealers.
   Earlier this month, he was suspended for five days over a school
assembly featuring a dancer who stripped her male partners down to
G-strings. He was not present and said the performance was done
without his knowledge.
   Bennett, who was secretary of education in the Reagan
administration before becoming head of President Bush's anti-drug
efforts, helped draw attention to Clark last year when he praised
his get-tough theories of school discipline.
</TEXT>
