<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Congress     03-18 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Congress,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>National People's Congress Opens Monday, Fight Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's legislature opens its annual meeting
Monday, and some observers expect a tough fight between delegates
calling for democratic change and government officials stressing
stability.
   The government argues that it needs stability to solve China's
pressing economic problems. Many intellectuals say the economic
problems will persist unless the government relaxes tight political
controls.
   Pro-democratic forces are expected to continue an open-letter
campaign, urging an amnesty for political prisoners and respect for
human rights.
   Since January, four such letters have been sent, signed by more
than 100 leading intellectuals. The last letter was sent last week,
despite threats of punishment by government officials.
   Delegates also said they expected the issue of human rights to be
raised at the congress itself, an unprecedented act of defiance.
   ``It will be a lively time,'' said one Communist Party member.
``Intellectuals will push as far as they can go.''
   Government officials have ordered the state-run media to censor
reports of disagreements at the 2,796-member National People's
Congress and portray the delegates as united, Communist Party
sources said.
   And the restrictions are apparently not limited to the domestic
press.
   On Friday night, Chinese authorites interrogated two Taiwanese
journalists after they had interviewed a delegate. Two teams of Hong
Kong reporters were also stopped from talking with delegates.
   Lu Zhichao, a government spokesman, apologized for the incidents,
but he said he could not assure it would not happen again.
   ``It will be a step back from last year,'' said one delegate.
   During last year's congress, the Chinese news media was allowed
to report some disagreements between delegates as part of the
state's attempt at openness.
   The government has been emphasizing that it needs stability to
solve China's weighty economic problems.
   By doing so, party sources said, China hopes to persuade wavering
delegates that it's best to remain quiet and follow the government
line.
   In an attempt at conciliation, the government has announced it
will appoint more members of democratic parties to government
positions. The first appointments were made Friday when
non-Communist Party members were appointed vice-minister of labor
and vice-minister of agriculture.
   Delegates said the appointments will be made to present an image
of democracy and to take some of the blame off the Communist Party
for failed policies.
   ``But it will fail,'' said one party member. ``All the delegates
know that the `democratic' parties are even more communist than the
Communist Party.''
   The congress is also expected to pass some laws, two of which are
critical to the reform of China's political system.
   One law gives civilians the right to sue the government. It has
been criticized by liberal thinkers because it does not acknowledge
that the government can break the law. But moderates have hailed it
as a step in the right direction.
   Another law delineates the powers of the congress, an important
step in reforms designed to separate the functions of the Communist
Party from the government.
   The congress opens against a backdrop of serious political and
economic problems.
   Inflation is running at a record 36 percent. Grain harvests have
been below target for the past five years. Electricity is in scarce
supply. Steel production has dropped. Salt and cotton are hard to
buy.
   Corruption among government officials and party members appears
at an all time high. Newspapers are filled with reports of official
malfeasance.
</TEXT>
