<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-USAmbassador     03-18 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-US Ambassador,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Welcomes Appointment Of Lilley As US Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Saturday welcomed President Bush's
selection of James R. Lilley as ambassador to Beijing.
   Lilley, born in China to American parents, was a former
intelligence officer in Beijing and worked in U.S. missions in
Taiwan and Hong Kong. He was ambassador to South Korea from 1986
until January.
   The White House announced Lilley's appointment Wednesday to
replace Winston Lord, who has been ambassador since 1985.
   ``We welcome the appointment by the U.S. President of Mr. James
Lilley as the U.S. Ambassador to China,'' China's Foreign Ministry
said in a one-sentence statement Saturday.
   Lilley's previous stint in Beijing came while Bush was U.S.
liaison officer in the Chinese capital in 1974-75, before the two
countries established full diplomatic relations in 1979.
</TEXT>
