<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Memorial     03-18 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Memorial,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latin American Memorial Opens in Sao Paulo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil Saturday unveiled Latin America's
largest cultural center, a complex of libraries, lecture halls and
galleries to bring together the region's artists, writers and
scientists.
   The eight futuristic, white concrete buildings _ known as the
Latin American Memorial _ were created by Brazilian architect Oscar
Niemeyer, who also designed the modernistic capital of Brasilia.
   Politicians and cultural figures from around Latin America
attended the inauguration, including Cuban Vice President Carlos
Rafael Rodriguez and former Chilean foreign minister Gabriel Valdez.
   In an interview with the O Estado de S. Paulo newspaper, Niemeyer
said the memorial was ``a call for the unity of the people of Latin
America so that together they can defend their rights and walk
together in the direction of social revolution.''
   The 100,000-square-yard memorial, which bears Niemeyer's
characteristic bold curves, archs and huge beams, cost the state of
Sao Paulo $37 million. It was built by Gov. Orestes Quercia.
   Anthropologist Darcy Ribeiro, the memorial's cultural affairs
adviser, said the complex will include the first library dedicated
exclusively to Latin America, with an initial collection of 30,000
books.
</TEXT>
