<FIRST>r i AM-Malaysia-Detainees     03-18 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-Detainees,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar Council Calls For Inquiry Into Claims Detainees Tortured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Malaysian association of lawyers
urged the government Saturday to investigate charges that some
political detainees have been tortured.
   The Bar Council also called for the repeal of the controversial
Internal Security Act, which allows indefinite detention without
charge, and for the government to lift restrictions imposed on some
of 106 political detainees freed during the past year.
   In a resolution at its annual meeting, the Bar Council said any
findings of an inquiry should be published, council President S.
Theivanthiran told reporters.
   The lawyers objected to restrictions under the act that included
bans on contact with reporters, compulsory monthly reports to
police, and travel limitations.
   Deputy Home Affairs Minister Megat Junid Megat Ayub told
Parliament on Friday that about 70 people still are detained under
the act.
   Some released detainees have said they were tortured while
imprisoned, but Megat denies the charges.
</TEXT>
