<FIRST>r a AM-TurkeyBowling     03-18 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey Bowling,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Butterball Firm Tells Turkey Bowler To Take His Sport And Split</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former supermarket clerk trying to
rise to fame with a sport called ``Turkey Bowling'' that he says he
invented has ruffled some feathers at the company that sells
Butterball brand turkeys.
   Executives at Chicago-based Swift-Eckrich are mad because every
time Derrick Johnson of Santa Ana shows up on television to ``bowl''
a frozen turkey at 2-liter plastic soda bottles, his bird of choice
is a 12-pound Butterball.
   Johnson, who thought up the pastime one night while stocking
turkeys at a supermarket, has demonstrated turkey bowling on
national television, including the syndicated ``Arsenio Hall Show''
and CBS's ``Sunday Morning.''
   But Swift-Eckrich told Johnson in a terse, four-paragraph letter
last month to stop using its turkeys because it ``damages the
Butterball quality image that we have spent millions of dollars to
develop.''
   The company threatened Johnson with a lawsuit and said it may
seek a court order to force him to quit using Butterballs and may
also seek damages.
   But Johnson, 29, a former Los Angeles Rams cheerleader and
Chippendales' nightclub dancer, refuses to abandon turkey bowling.
   ``No way!'' Johnson said Friday. ``This is my ticket into the big
time. If Swift-Eckrich wants me to stop, all they have to do is
write me a check. Better yet, why don't they hire me as their West
Coast spokesman. Apparently, I've done more to spread their name and
reputation than all their high-priced PR guys.''
   ``People ask why I don't use another turkey,'' Johnson said.
``Listen, I love Butterballs. That's all we had when I was growing
up. Let's just say I am a loyal customer.''
   He said he is too busy promoting his sport and himself to worry
about a lawsuit. He said he already has endorsements from a
sportswear and shoe company.
   He also is working with a local market to put on ``Grocery
Games,'' to raise money to buy food for the homeless.
   ``This is the sport of the '90s,'' Johnson said. ``I can see it
now. The party invitation will read: `BYOB _ Bring Your Own Bird.' ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
