<FIRST>r i AM-SealDemo     03-18 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seal Demo,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Say Hunters Slaughtering Even More Seals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hundred animal lovers demonstrated Saturday
against the slaughter of baby seals off Newfoundland's north coast,
saying it is worse now than when it was made illegal in 1982.
   Hunters have shifted their sights to pups older than nine days
since the 1982 legislation prohibited killing of ``white coats'' _
seals under that age, said a spokesman for demonstrators from
Montreal, Ottawa and Toronto, who marched peacefully around
Parliament building.
   ``That makes it even worse,'' said Stephen Best of Toronto, vice
president of the International Wildlife Coalition that organized the
protest.
   ``Where the `white coats' were taken on the pan ice around the
north shore of Newfoundland and just about all that were killed were
harvested, the hunt now is mainly at sea where it's estimated three
pups have to be killed for every one got into the boats.
   ``Now it's on the open seas where it is almost impossible to
regulate. There aren't any inspectors or scientists out there.
Nobody knows what's going on,'' he said.
   The harvest, which bottomed out at 20,000 seals a year right
after the legislation was enacted, since has risen to 80,000, Best
said.
   He also said the government issues 9,000 licenses a season to
hunt seals, compared to 5,000 before the legislation. The government
quota for this season is 186,000 harp seals and 2,340 hooded seals,
he said.
   ``We thought we had won in 1982, and so did everyone else,'' Best
recalls. ``But we didn't win; we lost. Now we've got to start all
over again.''
</TEXT>
