<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     03-18 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Takeover of Provincial Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels from the Sudan People's Liberation
Army on Saturday claimed they had taken the southern provincial
capital of Mongalla.
   The government did not confirm the reports, but Prime Minister
Sadek Mahdi on Saturday met with senior military and security
officials to review the situation in the province, Equatoria.
   The rebels, in a broadcast on their clandestine Radio Liberation,
said they took Mongalla from government troops on Friday. The
broadcast, monitored in Khartoum, did not give details of the
reported capture.
   The southern rebels, mostly Christians and animists, oppose the
government, which is deominated by the north's Moslem Arab majority.
They initiated the country's civil war in 1983 to push for greater
autonomy.
   Mahdi has been under pressure from the military and opposition
parties to include the rebels in a broad-based government coalition
and end the civil war. Mongalla was the capital of southern Sudan
under British rule, which ended in 1956.
</TEXT>
