<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     03-18 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Official: Geneva Accord Has Been Violated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORTEN HVAAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a U.N. office in
Afghanistan said Saturday that the pact that ended the Soviet
military involvement in the nation has been breached, but he would
not say who committed them or what they were.
   The comments came on the same day as at least four Soviet IL-76
military transports arrived in Kabul. The Soviets, which completed
its troop withdrawal last month, resumed military aid to the
government last week.
   The U.N. official, Maj. Gen. Rauli Helminen, said Pakistan and
Afghanistan have repeatedly charged each other with violating the
accord, but their complaints have often proved inaccurate. Others
are difficult to check, he told a news conference.
   Helminen heads the U.N. Good Offices Mission to Afghanistan and
Pakistan. It was set up to investigate alleged violations of the
Geneva Accord that cleared the way for the Red Army's departure
after nine years in Afghanistan.
   The mission is made up of about 40 officers from Austria, Canada,
Denmark, Fiji, Finland, Ghana, Iceland, Nepal, Poland and Sweden.
   ``There are problems. After 11 months, more than half of our
mandate remains unfulfilled,'' said Helminen, who is from Finland.
   Pakistan and Afghanistan agreed under the accord to stay out of
each other's internal affairs. But since then, he said, the Kabul
government has filed 3,000 complaints accusing Pakistan of violating
the accord by continuing to arm the Moslem insurgents and sending
hundreds of its soldiers into Afghanistan.
   Pakistan, which supports the Moslem guerrillas trying to
overthrow Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government, has lodged at
least 800 complaints against Afghanistan. Pakistan says Afghan
planes have bombed its territory in attacks on Moslem guerrilla
camps.
   The Kabul government has called on the United Nations to set up
checkpoints along the border. But Helminen said that will not happen
until warring Afghans call a cease-fire.
   The Soviets have said they will continue to supply equipment to
President Najib's troops as long as Pakistan and the United States
supply the guerrillas.
   The military supplies Moscow is supplying to Kabul include
medium-range Scud B missiles and other defensive arms.
   The Soviets resumed the military supplies after guerrillas
launched an offensive against Jalalabad in eastern Afghanistan.
After nearly two weeks, heavy fighting around the strategic city
appears to have reached a stalemate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
