<FIRST>r w AM-TerrorismWarnings 1stLd-Writethru a0531 03-18 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Terrorism Warnings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0531,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detailed Warnings On Flight 103 Bring Investigation, Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng ``The brother...'' to insert name of
man quoted; SUBS 20th graf to conform; picks up 21st graf pvs, bgng: ``The
group...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disclosures of detailed warnings in Europe
before the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland have prompted
calls for new investigations and appeals for more government
openness about terrorist threats.
   A congressional subcommittee analysis of Federal Aviation
Administration security warnings, due for release Sunday, will show
that many FAA warnings are ``woefully inadequate,'' according to a
committee staff member.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner dispatched top aides to
Europe this weekend to examine the growing controversy over the
warnings and to determine the safety of U.S. airlines from terrorist
attack.
   And, some of the relatives of the 270 people killed in the Dec.
21 disaster planned a White House protest April 3, the 103rd day
after the bombing.
   Bert Ammerman, the brother of one of those killed, pleaded: ``I'd
like the opportunity to make my own decison on whether I die on a
plane or not.''
   The latest actions follow revelations and discussions in London
and Washington about very specific warnings that airlines and
government officials were sharing in Europe and the United States in
the weeks before the bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   None of the information got to passengers.
   Pan Am, after it did warn passengers of a bomb threat against a
New York-Paris flight last week, said it has a long-standing policy
of advising travelers and giving them the option of taking other
flights when there is a specific threat against an individual flight.
   The Lockerbie disaster was not preceded by any reported threat
that named a specific plane.
   But disclosures over the past several weeks indicate that
authorities had several other warnings, including what airline and
flights might be endangered, in what month the bombing could occur,
what type of explosive and triggering device might be used and even
how the bomb might be concealed in a radio-cassette.
   Investigators concluded that a radio-cassette containing plastic
explosives set to go off at a certain altitude blew up Pan Am Flight
103.
   Both British aviation authorities and the Federal Aviation
Administration had described a radio-cassette bomb in security
warnings a month earlier, after one was confiscated in a raid in
West Germany on the Syrian-backed Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine-General Command.
   Pan Am acknowledges that it received a warning about such a
device from the West German government on Nov. 10.
   Various other warnings that have elements similar to what
occurred in the Pan Am bombing also were issued Dec. 5 to all
airlines, Dec. 13 to U.S. embassies, Nov. 17 to U.S. airlines, Nov.
22 to British airlines and Dec. 19 to British airports and several
airlines. Some of the warnings, including the final one two days
before the bombing, were not received for several days.
   Although investigators apparently have focused much of their
attention on the Palestinian guerrilla group which was the subject
of some of the warnings, British officials said Friday that contrary
to London press reports, they had not captured or identified any
suspected bomber.
   On Capitol Hill, where several committees have been examining
issues raised by the destruction of Flight 103, House Government
Operations subcommittee staff members were compiling 27 FAA security
warnings issued in 1988 and another four this year, most of them not
made public.
   The subcommittee planned to look into how each one was handled,
who was warned, when they were warned, and how the government and
airlines dealt with the threats, a subcommitee source said,
discussing the report on condition of anonymity.
   ``We are looking at their accuracy, timeliness and usefulness,''
the source said.
   The report is to focus particularly on the Nov. 17 warning
dealing with a radio-cassette bomb. The source said subcommittee
chairwoman Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., decided to conduct the
analysis because there of confusion about the warnings and a host of
complaints from victims' relatives and others.
   Ammerman, a New Jersey high school administrator who was one of
about 20 victims' relatives who met with Skinner, said the families
are calling for a ban on all batteries on airliners, because plastic
explosives cannot be set off without a battery.
   The group also wants a system set up so passengers can call a
number and find out about any threats, more efforts to match luggage
with passengers and routine questioning of passengers as they board
flights.
   ``At best, this has been handled in a chaotic way,'' said
Ammerman, whose brother Tom was killed in the bombing. ``At worst,
there's been a coverup.''
</TEXT>
