<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-18 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Develop In The East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms broke out Saturday in the East, ice coated highways
and powerlines in Michigan, and up to a foot of snow fell in the
mountains of northern California.
   Temperatures rose to record highs along the East Coast,
including: 82 in Baltimore; 70 in Hartford, Conn.; 78 in Newark,
N.J.; 77 in New York City; 78 in Philadelphia; and 77 in Wilmington,
Del.
   The collision of that moist, warm air with cold air from the
north set the stage for thunderstorms that developed along a cold
front extending from southern New England through much of the
Appalachian region and the Tennessee Valley.
   A thunderstorm in eastern Pennsylvania produced strong wind that
downed trees at Pottsville, and a thunderstorm in eastern West
Virginia produced wind gusts to 58 mph at Martinsburg, the National
Weather Service said.
   Behind the cold front, heavy snow blanketed parts of the
Northeast overnight, with snowfall totals by Saturday in Vermont
ranging up to 8 inches at Derby and 7 inches at Canaan.
   Freezing temperatures followed rain or snow across Michigan's
Lower Peninsula, glazing roads and downing power lines that cut
electrical service to up to 109,000 households, officials said.
Between 8 and 12 inches of snow fell Friday and early Saturday
across parts of the area.
   ``It's been awful, awful,'' said Michigan State Police Sgt. Chris
Ignaczak in Detroit, where at least 100 traffic accidents, one a
20-car chain collision, were reported between 2 a.m. and 11 a.m.
Saturday. No serious injuries were reported.
   In the West, a cold front spread rain over northern California
and the northern Pacific Coast region and snow fell at higher
elevations of northern California and western Nevada.
   Up to 10 inches of snow blanketed the Lake Tahoe area of Nevada
overnight, with 12 inches reported at Chester, Calif. Up to two feet
of snow was expected in the Lake Tahoe area by Sunday morning, along
with up to 3 feet of snow in the neighboring Sierra Nevada range.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees above zero at Warroad, Minn., to 89 at McAllen, Texas.
Saturday's low for the Lower 48 states was 16 below zero at Warroad.
   For Sunday, scattered showers were forecast from the northern and
central Pacific Coast across Idaho, Montana and Wyoming, with snow
over northwestern Wyoming and western and central Montana. Widely
scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast across Louisiana
and southern and central Texas. Widely scattered rain and snow
showers were forecast over the upper Great Lakes region and the
upper Mississippi Valley.
   Highs in the 20s and low 30s were predicted from Montana through
Minnesota to northern New England; in the 40s from the central
rockies through Minnesota and Iowa to the middle and northern
Atlantic Coast; above 70 from southern California through southern
and central Texas to Florida and southern Georgia; in the 80s across
the Florida Peninsula, in the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas, and
in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
