<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Slaying     03-18 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Slaying,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Intensifies Manhunt For Congressman's Assassin</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military and police intensified
the search Saturday for a gunman who killed a Filipino congressman
moments after the lawmaker arrived in the island province of
Masbate, police said.
   Special investigating teams from Manila and regional headquarters
were sent to the area and checkpoints were placed across the island
235 miles south of Manila, said Col. Marino Filart, regional
Philippine Constabulary commander.
   Rep. Moises Espinosa was the first member of Congress to be slain
since President Corazon Aquino took office in February 1986.
   Police said Espinosa, 55, was walking across the airport tarmac
to his car Friday when the gunman dressed in fatigues and sunglasses
opened fire with an AK-47 rifle and fled on a motorcycle with a
companion.
   Amado Gaspar, an Espinosa aide who was wounded in the ambush,
died early Saturday, police said. A provincial guard and an airport
employee also were killed and a student was wounded.
   Espinosa ran as an independent but later joined the Struggle of
the Democratic Filipino, which supports Mrs. Aquino. He was a member
of former President Ferdinand Marcos' New Society Movement party
until Marcos was ousted in a popular uprising three years ago.
