<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-Viewing     03-18 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Viewing,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Patriotic Cheers, Tears _ And a Monumental Traffic Jam</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flags waved, tears of pride
flowed and a spontaneous rendition of the national anthem broke out
in the desert dawn Saturday among the 450,000 people who watched the
return of the space shuttle Discovery.
   ``I'm just fascinated by it,'' said Bob Dube, 34, of Canyon
Country, Calif., a veteran of the temporary encampments that spring
up on Rogers Dry Lake here for landings of the winged spacecraft.
   The crowd, many of whom arrived earlier in the week, burst out in
whistles and cheers at the thump of two sonic booms that preceded
Discovery's arrival over this Mojave Desert base 60 miles north of
Los Angeles.
   About two minutes later the ship appeared, seemingly straight
overhead, as a speck glinting in the dawn sunlight. Most lapsed into
surprised silence at the shuttle's steep descent, but the
celebration resumed as Discovery landed on a strip about five miles
distant at 6:35 a.m. PST.
   Spectators clapped, whooped, snapped pictures and waved American
flags. Many spontaneously began singing the national anthem. Some
cried; others hugged their children.
   ``The patriotic spirit here is really something,'' said Ernie
Weiss, 70, of Garden Grove, who flew a flag atop a telescoping
60-foot pole. ``I even bought a new flag for this.''
   NASA officials estimated the crowd at the public viewing area at
450,000, and said an additional 10,000 watched at the NASA facility.
That was second only to the 500,000 who joined President Reagan to
watch shuttle Columbia's July 4, 1982, landing.
   Shortly after landing, the estimated 138,000 motorhomes, cars and
trucks jammed the two narrow, one-lane blacktop roads that led to
the nearest highway, 30 miles from the vewing site.
   Remembering the five-hour traffic jam that followed the last
landing, Dube was one of hundreds poised for a quick getaway, and
was on the road right after the shuttle touched down.
   ``It's Saturday. If it was a work day I'd hang around a little
longer,'' he said.
   Spectators began gathering earlier in the week to stake out prime
viewing spots. The came in flag-bedecked motorhomes, aboard
motorcycles, and in cars pulling travel trailers.
   As many as 300 people who arrived after roads to the base were
closed simply pulled off the highway and drove onto the desert to
watch the landing. Several got stuck or damaged their axles when
they accidentally drove into holes in the desert hardpan.
   On Friday, the strains of country music blared over loudspeakers
at the makeshift campground as military helicopters buzzed overhead
and skateboarders rattled across the hardened lake bed.
   Pat Tolner, 35, a nurse from Annapolis, Md., witnessed the
shuttle lift off Monday in Florida.
   ``My husband wanted to know what I wanted for Christmas and I
told him I wanted to see the shuttle take off,'' she said. ``I spent
the night in the car and watched it take off, and when I got home I
told him I wanted to see it land. I flew to California Wednesday. I
rented a car and here I am.''
   Many of the early arrivals were so-called ``snowbirds,'' retired
couples who spend their winters in warm climates.
   ``We winter in the South every year and we just had to see the
shuttle land,'' said 74-year-old Bill Henderson of Sunnyside, Wash.,
who arrived with his wife, Evelyn.
   ``I'm sure we'd see it better on TV, but we just had to be
here,'' he said.
</TEXT>
