<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Communists     03-18 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Communists,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party to Form Shadow Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's large Communist Party announced Saturday it
will form a shadow government to convince voters it could
effectively govern the country.
   Achille Occhetto, party secretary, said the shadow government
will be composed of both Communist Party officials and intellectuals
or other specialists, and it will put forth ``policy and
governmental proposals.''
   Occhetto outlined the proposal in a speech opening the 18th
congress of the Italian Communist Party, or PCI, which is the
country's second-largest party but has suffered a steady slide in
votes.
   Occhetto, who took the party reins last summer, called for a
change in the composition of Italy's government, which for four
decades has been dominated by the conservative Christian Democrats
while the Communists have been kept out of governing coalitions.
   He appealed for new alliances with Roman Catholic groups and with
lay parties, particularly the four parties in the current governing
coalition led by the Christian Democrats.
   He also said the increasingly popular Green Party should look
beyond ecological issues and team with parties committed to
widespread reform.
   Turning to foreign affairs, Occhetto said the Communists had a
clear commitment to Italy's alliances with the West, particularly
NATO.
   At the same time, he said, ``we want to develop in a more open
and rich way a policy of dialogue and collaboration ... with the
party of (Soviet President) Mikhail Gorbachev, and with other
Communist parties committed to the democratization of the countries
they govern.''
   The Italian Communist Party broke with the Soviet Union in the
1970s and has since pursued its own course, which included an effort
to rule with the Christian Democrats in the mid-70s. Occhetto
suggested Saturday that that effort _ known as the ``historic
compromise'' _ was mistaken.
   The party has declined steadily in the polls over the past
decade, winning just 26.6 percent of the vote in parliamentary
elections in 1987 after nearly overtaking the Christian Democrats in
1976.
   Communist party members gathered in a Rome convention hall
applauded Occhetto when he called for the political rehabilitation
of Alexander Dubcek, the former Czechoslovak Communist Party leader
who introduced the ill-fated ``Prague Spring'' reforms.
   Dubcek was invited to the congress but Czechoslovak authorities
did not grant him a visa.
</TEXT>
