<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SRP-Westinghouse     03-18 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SRP-Westinghouse,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: DOE Renegotiating With Incoming SRP Operator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Energy is
renegotiating its contract with the next operator of the Savannah
River Plant in an attempt to better influence how the nuclear
weapons facility is run, according to a report published Saturday.
   Westinghouse Electric Co. will assume operation of the plant from
Du Pont on April 1. Last year, Westinghouse won a five-year, $6.7
billion contract from the Energy Department to run SRP.
   DOE sources and U.S. Rep. Butler Derrick, D-S.C., said Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins wants to make the company more
accountable for its operations at the complex, The State newspaper
of Columbia reported Saturday.
   Officials said Watkins' goal is to ``restructure the
relationship'' between Westinghouse and the Energy Department, the
newspaper reported.
   Watkins reportedly wants to give the agency a more dominant role
and prevent a recurrence of operational problems that have plagued
Du Pont, which designed and built the 300-square-mile facility and
has operated it since 1950.
   All three reactors at the plant have been shut down since last
summer for safety upgrades, maintenance and establishment of new
operative procedures.
   The reactors are the nation's sole source of weapons-grade
tritium, a perishable gas vital to the production of nuclear
warheads.
   James Moore, president of Westinghouse Savannah River Co.,
acknowledged that the contract between the government and
Westinghouse is being renegotiated. He characterized the discussions
as amicable and said he saw no obstacle to completing them before
April 1.
   DOE officials and others have been alarmed by Westinghouse's
decision to bring in only 40 new managers at SRP after the company
had pledged to bring in ``several hundred,'' according to the
newspaper report.
   SRP has a total work force of about 17,000.
   ``My personal opinion is that 40 is not enough,'' said John
Ahearne, chairman of DOE's independent safety panel and former
chairman of the federal Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   But Troy Wade, acting assistant secretary for the Energy
Department's defense program, said Friday he is satisfied that
Westinghouse will fulfill its commitments.
</TEXT>
