<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-SynagogueAttack     03-18 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Synagogue Attack,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Goes on Trial In Absentia For Synagogue Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese Palestinian went on trial in absentia
Saturday on charges of organizing the 1982 attack on Rome's main
synagogue that killed a 2-year-old boy and wounded 37 people.
   Abdel Osama Zomar was to be extradited from Greece to stand
trial, but the Greek government decided last December to deport him
to the country of his choice, saying he had been ``acting in the
struggle for the reacquisition of his country.'' He went to Libya.
   Police have not identified the gunmen who hurled grenades and
fired submachine guns at the synagogue on Oct. 9, 1982.
   Judges at Rome's criminal court questioned witnesses Saturday and
accepted a petition from Italy's Jewish community to be considered a
civil plaintiff in the case.
   Zomar, an alleged member of the terrorist faction led by Abu
Nidal, was arrested on the Greek-Turkish border in November 1982
while driving a car loaded with explosives.
   He was sentenced to 20 months for arms smuggling but remained
jailed during the long extradition process.
   The Greek supreme court approved an Italian extradition request
in November 1984 but it was never carried out. The extradition was
later overturned by the Greek justice minister, a decision protested
by Italy, the United States and Israel.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri Banna, split with the
Palestine Liberation Organization in the early 1970s and heads a
group called the Fatah Revolutionary Council. His group is
responsible for attacks on Rome and Vienna airport in December 1985
that left a total of 20 people dead.
</TEXT>
