<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica-Soweto     03-18 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Soweto,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Leaders Seek To Unify Soweto and Johannesburg</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid leaders in
Soweto say a prolonged rent boycott is likely to continue until the
vast black township is unified economically and politically with
neighboring Johannesburg.
   A committee of activists, including Anglican Archbishop Desmond
Tutu, concluded in a new report that Soweto will never be able to
pay off a $300 million debt accumulated since most families stopped
paying rent and service charges in 1986.
   The committee is urging the white-controlled government to write
off the debt and create a single tax base for Johannesburg and
Soweto so money spent by blacks in Johannesburg can be returned to
their own community for development and services.
   ``No development policy for Soweto will succeed until
Johannesburg and Soweto are treated as one urban economy,'' said the
Rev. Frank Chikane, chairman of the seven-member committee, at a
news conference Thursday.
   Chikane, general-secretary of the South African Council of
Churches, said the proposal represents a fundamental challenge to
apartheid because a unified economy would entail a unified political
entity.
   ``The demand is actually for a normal country with normal
cities,'' he said. ``The system must be deracialized.''
   An estimated 2.5 million blacks live in Soweto, the country's
largest municipality. The white population of Johannesburg and its
adjacent suburbs is about 600,000.
   The rent boycott, launched to press grievances against the
government, has evolved into one of the most effective forms of
protest available to blacks under the 33-month-old state of
emergency.
   Authorites have used numerous tactics in futile attempts to break
the boycott, including late-night eviction raids such as one in
August 1986 that led to the deaths of nearly 30 blacks in a clash
with police.
   Chikane's committee said the Soweto town council should write off
rental arrears owed by householders, implement affordable service
charges, and establish a formula for transferring ownership of
rented homes to long-term occupants.
   A study released by the committee said Sowetans spend $400
million annually in Johannesburg, generating tax revenue that
benefits white residents without returning to Soweto.
   According to the study, businesses provide about 70 percent of
Johannesburg's tax revenue, enabling white homeowners to pay lower
service fees than Sowetans yet get better services.
   Compared to Johannesburg, Soweto has only a handful of licensed
businesses. The most common businesses in the township are
unlicensed grocery stores and pubs which pay no taxes.
   Chikane's committee already has met with the Soweto town council
and hopes to arrange a further meeting. The activists also want to
confer with the Johannesburg City Council.
   Soweto mayor, Sam Mkhwanazi has surprised the activists by
acknowledging their influence in the community. The committee
includes the general-secretary of the black miners' union, Cyril
Ramaphosa, and Albertina Sisulu, wife of jailed African National
Congress leader Walter Sisulu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
