<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     03-18 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detain seven mine executives as strike by ethnic Albanians continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police detained seven executives of
the Stari Trg lead mine in Kosovo province where ethnic Albanian
workers have been on strike for more than three weeks, Belgrade
television reported Saturday.
   The miners have ignored a federal order to return to work. They
went on strike Feb. 21 to protest planned constitutional changes
they say would limit the province's autonomy.
   Kosovo, where 85 percent of the people are ethnic Albanians, is
an administrative part of Serbia, Yugoslavia's largest republic.
   The television report said the seven detained executives are
ethnic Albanians accused of counterrevolutionary activities and they
would be held for a month while an investigation continues.
   Two other directors of the Stari Trg mine were detained earlier
his month in what was seen as an effort to get the strikers to
return to work.
   Reports from Kosovo said that on Friday only ten maintenance
employees were on duty at the Stari Trg mine that has a normal work
force of 1,300.
   Hundreds of workers at the nearby Goles and Kisnica mines have
joined the strike.
   A compulsory work order was issued by Yugoslavia's federal
government on Feb. 27.
   The Tanjug news agency reported that Albanian students in Kosovo
were attending classes but refusing to speak.
   It also said Friday three students were sentenced to prison by a
court in Prizren, Kosovo's capital, for disseminating hostile
propaganda to ``destroy unity.'' It said the students of Albanian
descent were given sentences ranging from three to four years.
   The Kosovo Parliament is scheduled to meet on March 24 to approve
changes in the provincial constitution that would give Serbia much
greater control over the region.
</TEXT>
