<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     03-18 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Issues New Security Orders to its Carriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New security orders have been issued to all of
Britain's major airports, a Manchester airport spokesman said
Saturday. The orders came amid controversy over warnings received
before the December bombing of Pan Am Flight 103.
   The British news media said it was believed the new directive
requires passengers to remove all electric and electronic equipment
from luggage before check-in and to pack such items in hand luggage
to be examined at boarding gates.
   Investigators have said the bomb that blew up Flight 103 on Dec.
21 over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing all 259 people on the plane and
11 on the ground, was concealed in a radio-cassette player.
   A Manchester airport spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping
with British practice, said the orders were received Friday night
but he could not give details because it was a security matter.
   The Department of Transport would not say if a new directive had
been sent. But it reaffirmed a Feb. 18 message that advised all
airlines using British airports to begin asking travelers if their
baggage contained radios, computers or such equipment and then to
examine the items for possible explosives.
   The message did not say if examined items should be carried as
hand baggage or be checked through with other luggage.
   The Conservative Party government of Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher came under renewed attack Saturday for its handling of a
bomb warning before Flight 103 blew up.
   It was disclosed Friday that the Transport Department had
prepared a warning dated Dec. 19 that included photographs of a bomb
disguised in a radio-cassette player, but it did not mail the
advisory until after Christmas.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon said the advice was of little
importance because similar information had been disseminated a month
earlier by the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration and by West
Germany.
   Flight 103 originated in West Germany and changed planes at
London's Heathrow airport before departing for New York.
   Early editions of two Sunday newspapers, The Observer and The
Sunday Telegraph, said the Dec. 19 warning carried several details
that would have helped security people spot a rigged radio-cassette
player.
   The Sunday Telegraph quoted Channon as saying, ``Yes, maybe the
security information contained in the December 19 letter should have
been sent out by telex. The reason this was not done was because the
crucial element of the message consisted of a color photograph of a
possible explosive device.''
   The opposition Labor Party on Saturday repeated its request for
an independent inquiry into the Flight 103 disaster. John Prescott,
Labor's transport spokesman, said Channon had caused ``muddle and
confusion'' over the issue of warnings.
   ``The relatives of those who died in the Lockerbie disaster have
the right to expect a full and open account of how the government
responded from the moment it received the warnings of a possible
terrorist attack,'' he said.
   Channon responded by saying Prescott was using the situation ``to
try and make party political points of the worst possible kind,
preying on the grief of bereaved people.
   ``We're trying to get to the bottom of this,'' Channon said on a
British Broadcasting Corp. broadcast.
   Conservative legislator Robert Adley on Friday replied to
criticism from the opposition and from families of the victims. He
said ``malicious Labor politicians, hysterical Americans and
news-hungry media'' had united in a ``witch hunt aimed at the
Conservative government in general and the secretary of state for
transport in particular.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
