<FIRST>r a AM-ElSalvadorProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0585 03-18 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-El Salvador Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0585,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Protesters Rally Against U.S. Involvement in El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with rallies in Chicago, San Francisco,
Providence, New Jersey; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 60 people were arrested Saturday when protesters
gathered in several cities and at a New Jersey military base to
protest U.S. involvement in El Salvador.
   Police arrested 28 people in Chicago, where about 250
demonstrators turned out in front of the Chicago Tribune offices,
and 40 people in New Jersey, where more than 300 demonstrators
marched on McGuire Air Force Base.
   In New York, more than 1,200 sign-waving protesters marched on
Times Square. No arrests were reported. Smaller demonstrations were
held in San Francisco and Providence, R.I.
   Leslie Schuld, an organizer of the Chicago demonstration, said
there were 60 such rallies being held across the country, but that
figure could not be independently confirmed. The actions were timed
to coincide with the presidential elections in El Salvador,
scheduled for Sunday.
   In New York, demonstrators gathered in Union Square, where they
heard a speech from Arnoldo Ramos of the FMLN-FDR, the Salvadoran
rebel alliance. U.S. Rep. Major Owens, D-N.Y., addressed the group
when it arrived in Times Square.
   ``It's going quite well. The feelings here are quite strong,''
said Michael D'Elia, spokesman for the New York Coalition to Stop
the U.S. War in El Salvador.
   The rally was to be followed by civil disobedience on Monday,
with protesters blockading a federal building in lower Manhattan.
   ``The Bush administration (must) choose between negotiations or
an escalation of U.S. military involvement,'' said coalition
coordinator Miguel Ramirez. ``Many fear a Vietnam-like disaster if
the administration chooses the latter course.''
   The rally in New Jersey was orderly at first, with 300 to 400
people gathering outside the front gate of the Air Force base in
southern New Jersey, base spokesman Ken Bogdan said.
   However, he said some protesters began climbing over gates and
fences to get into the base, and then sat down and refused to move.
Some were carried away, Bogdan said. No injuries were reported.
   ``The point of the demonstration was to be arrested to show we
are resisting the war with our bodies and feel so strongly against
this U.S.-financed war in El Salvador,'' said coalition spokeswoman
Kate Woods.
   Of the 28 people arrested in Chicago, three were charged with
disorderly conduct and the rest were charged with obstructing
traffic on Michigan Avenue, said police Sgt. Robert McCracken.
   Ms. Schuld said the demonstrators hoped to ``send a strong
message to the Bush administration and Congress to support peace in
El Salvador.''
   ``We're just not going to let business go on as usual,'' she
said, adding ``$3.6 billion has been sent to El Salvador over the
last eight years to support death squads.''
   The rally was held at the Tribune Tower to underline what Ms.
Schuld called ``very weak'' press coverage of events in the Central
American nation.
   In San Francisco, about 150 protesters marched in the rain from
the largely Hispanic Mission District to the Federal Building. No
one was arrested.
   About 100 people gathered in Providence to hear speakers at a
morning meeting at The First Baptist Church before a march to the
Providence Journal-Bulletin building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
