<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Airbus     03-18 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Airbus,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Denounces World Air Group's Decision Not to Condemn U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's prime minister on Saturday
denounced the International Civil Aviation Organization's refusal to
condemn the United States for downing an Iranian airliner last July,
killing all 290 people aboard.
   Official Tehran radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Mir Hussein
Musavi as saying that ``if anywhere in the world an American had
lost a little blood, these same international organizations and
global communities would not let go of the matter.
   ``But the killing of 290 people ... is shirked away by a simple
apology,'' the radio quoted Musavi as saying.
   The U.N. agency made its declaration in Montreal Friday after an
eight-month examination of the incident, in which the USS Vincennes
shot down the airliner after mistaking it for an attacking Iranian
warplane.
   The agency rejected the request for censure by the Soviet Union
and Czechoslovakia. Without blaming any country, it adopted a
resolution that reaffirmed its policy of condemning the use of
weapons against civil aircraft.
   The agency deplored ``the tragic incident which occurred as a
consequence of events and errors in identification of the aircraft.''
   Edmund Stohr, the U.S. representative to ICAO, applauded the
decision, calling it ``a judgment that is balanced and treats the
truth fairly.''
   Musavi was quoted as saying the agency's refusal to denounce the
United States showed that ``the law of the jungle rules in the
international organizations, and our nation rejects this domination
(of) strength.''
</TEXT>
