<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Nuclear Plant,0117</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian Nuclear Plant Shut Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear power plant near an earthquake zone in
Armenia was closed permanently Saturday, but nuclear fuel will
remain at the site for three more years, Tass said.
   The Soviet Council of Ministers decided in January to close the
plant outside the Armenian capital of Yerevan after a killer
earthquake Dec. 7 killed 25,000 people just 25 miles away.
   Local environmentalists had fought to close the plant for years.
   Closure of the two-unit power plant is expected to cause power
shortages throughout Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia.
   Authorities have said they will increase electricity supplies
from conventional generators in the region.
