<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     03-18 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Records of Historic Forum On Eurocommunism to Be Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The records of a historic 1956 forum of
Hungarian intellectuals who espoused views later known as
Eurocommunism will be published this year, speakers at an academic
meeting said Saturday.
   In 1956, before the uprising against Communist rule that same
year, a circle of university students and other intellectuals
organized seven gatherings to discuss a variety of political,
economic and cultural themes.
   Texts of the lectures and debates of the Petoefi Circle, named
after the 19th century poet Sandor Petoefi, have never been
published.
   The forum proposed reforms adopted by the Eurocommunists more
than 10 years later. Eurocommunism advocated independence from the
Soviet Union and democratic elections.
   Speakers at Saturday's meeting of about 500 people, including
many Petoefi Circle supporters, said the full minutes of the forum
would be published between June and September.
   The meeting, called to discuss the importance of the Petoefi
Circle in Hungary's contemporary history, was announced in the
Hungarian press, which has recently become increasingly open.
   One of the organizers was Andras Hegedues, a sociologist who was
prominently involved in the 1956 forum and kept records of the
debates for eventual publication.
   ``We wanted reforms, we certainly did not want a
counterrevolution, but it should also be admitted that we did not
want a revolution either,'' Hegedues told participants.
   The 1956 uprising has officially been described as a
counterrevolution designed to break Communist rule. But Politburo
member Imre Pozsgay and other reformers have called it a popular
uprising, setting off a fierce debate in the party on the sensitive
issue.
   A recent party Central Committee session issued a statement
saying the 1956 revolt began as a popular uprising but later turned
into a counterrevolution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
