<HEAD>Robber Holds Judge Who Sentenced Him Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted robber held a judge
hostage for four hours after she gave him an eight-year prison
sentence, news reports said Saturday.
   Police later overpowered the man and freed the judge.
   Luka Bosnjak, 29, serving a five-year term for previous offenses,
was being tried by judge Vesna Benjak for hostage-taking while in
prison, the news reports said. The trial was in the northern town of
Varazdin.
   When the judge announced her verdict, lengthening Bosnjak's
remaining term from four to 12 years, the convict apparently went
beserk, the reports said. He broke away from his guards, grabbed the
judge, held a knife to her throat, ordered the courtroom emptied and
demanded a getaway car with a driver, a rifle with 10 bullets and
$1,250.
   After four hours, special police units managed to overpower the
man and free the judge, the reports said. The judge suffered minor
cuts on her palms.
   Other details of the courtroom drama were not reported.
