<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 2154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Thornburgh-Mafia     03-18 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Mafia,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Thornburgh To Dismantle Anti-Mafia Strike Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh tentatively has
decided to abolish most or all of the government's special strike
forces established decades ago to fight the Mafia, according to a
published report.
   In its Sunday editions, The New York Times reported that
Thornburgh is planning to dismantle the 24 regional Organized Crime
Strike Forces because he believes the job can best be done by local
U.S. attorneys.
   Thornburgh told the Times in an interview that the problem with
strike forces ``is that they are an independent field office of the
Department of Justice that competes with the U.S. attorneys.''
   The proposal is supported by most of the nation's 94 U.S.
attorneys but is meeting resistance from about 130 strike force
attorneys, the Times said.
   The strike force lawyers argue that U.S. attorneys have limited
resources for combating organized crime and that they lack personnel
familiar with or experienced with dealing with such activity, the
newspaper reported.
   The proposal, which is under study by Edward S.G. Dennis, head of
the Justice Department's criminal division, already has the
tentative approval of Thornburgh, the paper reported.
   Dennis strongly advocates abolishing the strike forces, the paper
said.
   The local U.S. attorneys are pressing for a system similar to one
already in use in the Southern District of New York, where the
strike force attorneys were merged into the local office and no
longer reported directly to Washington D.C.
   Supporters of the New York system credit it for allowing former
U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani to successfully prosecute several
Mafia cases.
   In the interview, Thornburgh said he would prefer to replace the
strike forces with a ``cadre of experienced prosecutors'' who could
be dispatched to work with local U.S. attorneys when needed.
   The Times said Thornburgh will decide the future of the strike
forces in a few weeks.
   The strike forces originated in the 1960s under then-U.S.
Attorney General Robert Kennedy. The strike forces were to marshal
the resources of the FBI, other federal agencies, local law
enforcement agencies in ridding Mafia influence in a region.
   The strike forces operated out of Washington D.C. because most
organized crime activity extends beyond state borders.
   Thornburgh's proposal is not new. Former Attorney General Edwin
Meese unsuccessfully tried to dismantle the strike forces.
   Thornburgh was a U.S. attorney in Pittsburgh from 1969 to 1974.
As a prosecutor there, he gained attention by jailing many
middle-level members of the Mafia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890318-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MalpracticeAward     03-18 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malpractice Award,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disabled Woman Awarded $10 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was left severely brain damaged and a
quadriplegic after going to a hospital for treatment of a broken leg
has been awarded $10 million in a medical malpractice suit.
   The award to Blanca Lilliana Naranjo, 21, was handed down this
week by a Dade County Circuit Court jury following a two-week trial.
Her suit alleged negligence on the part of South Miami Hospital and
its doctors and nurses.
   Ms. Naranjo, then 18, was riding her bicycle when she was struck
by a hit-and-run driver on April 22, 1986. She was admitted to the
hospital's intensive care unit for treatment of her leg fracture and
developed a complication known as fat embolism syndrome.
   The condition causes a buildup of fluid in the lungs, interfering
with breathing.
   Her lawyer, Michael Mullen, said the condition is not an uncommon
reaction to a broken leg and can be corrected with oxygenation and
ventilation if recognized in time. But he said the hospital's
doctors failed to identify the condition until she had gone into
cardiac arrest.
   ``She was in a coma for 2{ months,'' Mullen said, and ``left a
permanent, total 100 percent disabled spastic quadriplegic with
brain damage.''
   The Colombian native, who had been an honor student fluent in
three languages, was hospitalized more than eight months and now can
only speak a few words, Mullen said. Ms. Naranjo has $1.1 million in
hospital bills and will need complete care the rest of her life,
Mullen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
