<FIRST>r i AM-India-AirShow     03-18 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Air Show,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian air force displays combat aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TILPAT AIRFIELD, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Indian air force on Saturday
displayed its firepower and tactical skills with some of the Soviet
Union's most sophisticated combat aircraft.
   About 200 guests, including representatives from the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization and the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact, were at
the training field for the two-hour demonstration. Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi, a former pilot, watched through binoculars.
   Defense Ministry officials said the demonstration was to show the
capabilities of the country's combat planes and to encourage young
men to consider a military career. The air show was televised
nationally.
   India has 115,000 men and more than 700 aircraft in its air
force. Most of the planes were acquired from the Soviets.
   Foreign military experts have rated the skills of Indian air
force pilots as among the world's best, but they give the service
low marks for aircraft maintenance, citing the lack of engineers and
delays in obtaining spare parts.
   Flying 124 planes from 10 bases in the states of Uttar Pradesh,
Haryana and Punjab, the air force opened the show with supersonic
runs by European-made Jaguar and Soviet-made MiG-27 jet fighters and
a flyover by MiGs and French-made Mirage 2000s.
   In New Delhi, 17 miles away, windows and walls in some houses
rattled from the sound waves.
   The pilots demonstrated an array of ground-attack weapons,
including cluster bombs and 57mm rockets, but smoke forced officials
to scratch at least two of the 12 events and parts of others because
pilots could not see the targets.
</TEXT>
