<FIRST>r a AM-Chiropractor-Demons     03-18 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chiropractor-Demons,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chiropractor Ordered To Stop Blaming Demons For Clients' Health Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chiropractor has agreed to stop
advising patients their health problems are caused by demons, evil
spirits or other supernatural creatures, a state official said.
   Lee Walden, owner of a chiropractic clinic that bears his name,
also was placed on six months probation and agreed to stop
advertising and performing a sinus treatment in which a balloon is
inserted into the nose and inflated until it bursts, said Jim
Gallagher, a deputy attorney general for consumer protection.
   The agreement between Walden, the State Board of Chiropractic
Examiners and the state Attorney General's Office was signed March
10, Gallagher said Friday. It culminated a three-year investigation
in which Walden was ordered to undergo a psychiatric examination, he
added.
   The attorney general's office first sought an emergency
suspension of Walden's license in January 1986 after a woman filed a
complaint alleging that the chiropractor had blamed a patient's
overeating on possession by demons, according to state records.
Walden also told the woman her husband and her mother were
possessed, records show.
   The chiropractic board blocked that suspension. However, a
follow-up investigation revealed Walden had used the balloon
treatment and advertised it in the Yellow Pages between 1983 and
1987. He also had told patients their health problems were caused by
demonic possessions, the investigation found.
</TEXT>
