<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Bishops     03-18 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Bishops,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anglican Leaders Support Nicaraguan Government Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Anglican church officials led by
South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu backed the Sandinista
government's recent reform measures Saturday and called on
Washington to help resettle the rebels.
   The clerics, who arrived in Nicaragua Tuesday, issued a statement
that was read by the Rev. Edmond Browning, primate of the Episcopal
Church of the United States.
   The statement asked that funds provided by the U.S. government to
help Honduras-based Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, ``be used
to repatriate or relocate (the rebels) in other countries.''
   It said, ``We reject using this aid to maintain the Contras in
Honduras.''
   The Central American presidents signed a peace proposal Feb. 14
that seeks ways to disband the Contras and promote democratic
reforms by Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   Washington has supported the rebels since 1981 and the U.S.
Congress is set to vote next month on additional humanitarian aid to
the estimated 11,000 Contras in Honduras. President Bush is asking
about $4 million a month for the rebels.
   Browning said he will carry a message back to Bush based on his
observations.
   ``I hope that I will be able to do it in a manner that he will
understand,'' Browning said.
   Tutu, winner of the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize for his active
opposition against South Africa's policy of segregation, headed the
delegation that came to Nicaragua at the invitation of the Rev.
Sturdie Downs, bishop of Nicaragua's Episcopal Church.
   The delegation's statement praised recent measures taken by the
government as contributing to ``reconciliation and peace.''
   Among those measure was the release last week of nearly 1,900
former national guardsmen and the decision to allow 10 clergymen to
return to Nicaragua. Most of the guardsmen had been in prison since
the Sandinistas won a civil war and ousted the conservative
government of President Anastasio Somoza in July 1979.
   Browning said his visit to Nicaragua ``will cause certain
conflicts among members of the Episcopal Church'' in the United
States but he added he would be willing to return to Nicaragua ``to
help the people in the reconstruction of their faith as well as
social justice.''
   Members of the Anglican group met with President Daniel Ortega,
leaders of the political opposition, religious officials and
newspaper editors. They also visited the Caribbean coastal city of
Bluefields to see the damage cause by Hurricane Joan last October.
   They travel to Panama on Sunday.
</TEXT>
