<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-Drugs     03-18 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Drugs,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Czar Plans Strike Force to Combat Drugs in Washington DC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National drug director William J. Bennett is
making plans for a federal-local strike force to give ``shock
treatment'' to drug-infested areas of Washington D.C., according to
a published report.
   Bennett, who was sworn in Monday as the nation's first director
of national drug control policy, had said he may make the District
of Columbia a ``test case'' in the war against drugs. The district
has had 114 murders so far this year as Saturday, and most were
drug-related.
   The Washington Post, in Sunday's editions, quoted aides to
Bennett as saying that the strike force would target repeat drug
offenders and try to shut down the city's 90 open-air drug markets.
   Also, abandoned military facilities could be converted into
temporary prisons to provide more space to house the large number of
drug offenders officials expect to arrest during the anticipated
crackdown, the newspaper said.
   The paper quoted a source as saying that the strike force, which
could be created as soon as next month, would perform simultaneous
drug busts in specific neighborhoods. ``These are going to be
targeted operations . . . We're not just going to commit 5,000
people to the streets of D.C.,'' the source said.
   The Antidrug Abuse Act of 1988 authorizes Bennett to declare
certain cities ``high intensity drug trafficking areas'' and to
temporarily reassign federal personnel to those areas to work with
state and local officials.
   Some local law enforcement officials have questioned if the
district qualifies as a ``high intensity'' drug area.
   However, District Police Chief Maurice T. Turner Jr. said the
plan was ``encouraging news... We arrest them but they don't go to
jail, they don't fear jail. If the federal government assists us by
sending them to jail, it certainly will help.''
   Bennett had said Friday he did not plan to displace the local
police department, but that the federal government would seek to aid
local efforts.
   The strike force will include agents borrowed from the Federal
Bureau of Investigation, the Drug Enforcement Agency, the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and the U.S. Marshals Service, as well
as district and county police departments, the paper said.
   Bennett appointed Sherwood ``Chuck'' Wexler to serve as a liaison
for the agencies and a draft of the plan is expected within three
weeks, with a formal announcement to come later.
</TEXT>
