<FIRST>r a AM-TortureTrial     03-18 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Torture Trial,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Rejects Insanity Plea in Torture Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Circuit Court jury ruled Saturday that John
R. Weber was sane during the torture-murder of his sister-in-law in
1986 and an attempt to murder his wife two years later.
   The jury's rejection of Weber's insanity plea means he faces a
mandatory sentence of life in prison for first-degree murder rather
than commitment to a mental institution.
   Weber, 25, of Phillips, could also get up to 300 years in prison
for other crimes related to the attacks on the two women.
   Weber, who worked as a maker of Christmas wreaths, mutilated and
killed his wife's sister, Carla Lenz, 17, in 1986, and eventually
described the slaying in a tape recording with which to intimidate
his wife, police testified.
   The missing girl's grave was not discovered until police began
investigating a beating that sent his wife to a hospital last
September.
   His 22-year-old wife and his mother were in the courtroom during
Saturday's psychiatric testimony and closing arguments.
   The psychiatric testimony marked the trial's second phase. In the
first phase, the jury found Weber guilty of mutilating and sexually
assaulting Miss Lenz. Saturday it ruled him sane on the same charges
after deliberating 1{ hours.
   Weber had pleaded guilty to kidnapping and murdering Miss Lenz
and attempting to murder his wife on Sept. 3, 1988, near her
sister's grave. He later pleaded innocent by reason or mental
disease or defect to all charges.
   Judge Gary Carlson set no date for sentencing. Defense attorney
John Reid said he intended to appeal the verdicts in both trial
phases.
</TEXT>
