<FIRST>r a AM-TheBigOne     03-18 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-The Big One,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake-Simulating Ride Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ride that simulates the effects
of a massive earthquake on a San Francisco subway station opened
Saturday on the Universal Studios tour.
   The $13 million attraction, called the ``Big One,'' is designed
to mimic a quake of magnitude 8.3 on the Richter scale, estimated by
seismologists to equal the magnitude of the devastating 1906 San
Francisco shock.
   Universal Studios tram riders are treated to fears of unstable
earth, live burial, electrocution, fire, drowning, darkness and
abandonment in just two minutes, 25 seconds.
   ``We outlined seven basic terrors we wanted to scare up in the
tourists,'' said ride designer Larry Lester, who did the set for the
1974 movie ``Earthquake.'' ``We want people to run the gamut from
uncertainty about what's happening to them, to disbelief to absolute
fright.''
   Attendance at the amusement park was estimated at 22,000,
according to Universal spokesman Jim Yeager.
   That was about double the previous Saturday's attendance, but
Yeager said it wasn't possible to tell how many were attracted to
the jolting ride. Saturday also was the beginning of Easter Vacation
for many youths, he added.
</TEXT>
