<HEAD>Barbara Still Loves George But Millie's Expecting So He's Sleeping
Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts top two grafs to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millie, the first dog, is expecting pups any
day and doesn't like her new digs, so Barbara Bush has banished the
president to Abe Lincoln's bedroom.
   So, President Bush said Friday, he's spending the night alone.
   ``The dog refuses to go to the doghouse is the problem,'' Bush
told reporters traveling with him on Air Force One.
   Bush, who spent Thursday night in a hotel room in Colorado
Springs, Colo., said he has been banished by his wife, Barbara, from
sleeping in their usual bed in the White House.
   He said, instead, he would sleep in the historic Lincoln Bedroom
several doors away.
   He told reporters that, when he called the first lady, ``Barbara
told me `Tonight, you're in the Lincoln bed _ alone.' I said `why?'
She said, `well, Millie had a very bad night last night thrashing
around. And you would be irritable.'''
   ``So I'm being sent down the hall _ which just suits me fine.''
   Millie, an English spaniel, is due to have her pups at any
moment. Bush said, judging from her size, he guesses that the dog
will have about six puppies _ and he'll be glad when it's all over.
   He said that the dog adamantly refuses to use ``a beautiful pen
made for her to have this blessed event in,'' and insists on
remaining in the White House master bedroom.
   ``I never thought we'd go through something like this again _
after six kids and 11 grandchildren. But it's a whole new thing.''
   Bush said that the upcoming event is complicated by the
attachment that exists between the first lady and the first dog.
   ``She can't move without the dog being 10 feet way from her,''
Bush grumbled.
   But, he added, ``it's exciting.''
