<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Mitchell     03-18 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mitchell,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock 'n' Roll Pioneer Bobby Mitchell Dead at 53</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bobby Mitchell, who as a young musician helped
introduce rock 'n' roll into American pop culture, died early Friday
of kidney failure. He was 53.
   ``He was the godfather of rock and roll in New Orleans,'' said
the Duke-a-Paducah, Vernon C. Dugas, Mitchell's manager and a disc
jockey on a local public radio station.
   Mitchell, performing with his band The Toppers, had more than a
dozen hits on the Billboard Top 100 from 1952-62.
   His first record was ``I'm Crying,'' and his recording of ``Try
Rock and Roll'' was one of the first nationally released songs to
use the expression rock 'n' roll.
   ``He was one of the pioneers of rhythm and blues, and he should
be remembered as that,'' said Robert Vernon, a local music producer.
   Mitchell was probably best known for his hit, ``I'm Going to Be a
Wheel Someday,'' which was later covered by Fats Domino, another New
Orleans rhythm and blues man.
   Mitchell had been on a kidney dialysis machine for 10 years and
died at JoEllen Smith Hospital.
   A re-release of his early hits in 1979 brought him back into
performing. His last live show was at the New Orleans Jazz Fest last
year when friends carried him on to the stage.
</TEXT>
