<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Scandal     03-18 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Takeshita's Popularity Dives To 15 Per Cent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll released Saturday indicated support of Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita has plunged to 15 percent with his
government embroiled in a stock trading scandal and planned sales
tax.
   The poll was published by a leading newspaper, the Asahi Shimbun,
which said in an editorial: ``Taking account of Takeshita's support
rate, no one would be surprised if his Cabinet should resign at any
time.''
   It said 3,000 adults throughout the nation were polled March 15
and 16 and support of Takeshita's government dropped to 15 percent
from 28 percent in January. The newspaper did not list a margin of
error in the poll.
   The editorial said it is ``indispensable to reconstruct politics
from the beginning'' by dissolving Parliament and holding general
elections.
   Takeshita's Liberal Democratic Party government passed an
unpopular 3 percent consumption tax that will go into effect April 1
and proscutors have arrested 12 people in the stock profiteering
scandal.
   The scandal centers around an information conglomerate, Recruit
Co., which offered hundreds of thousands of unlisted shares in its
real estate subsidiary to more than 150 people, including political
and business leaders.
   Takeshita's former finance minister was among three government
officials who resigned in the scandal.
   The Asahi Shimbun poll gave Takeshita the third lowest rating in
Japan's post-World War II history. Public support was polled at only
12 percent for prime ministers Nobusuke Kishi in 1960 and Kakuei
Tanaka in 1974. Kishi had pushed through Parliament a revision of
the Japan-U.S. Security Treaty and Tanaka was connected to a bribery
case involving the U.S.-based Lockheed Corp.
   The opposition on Friday demanded again that Takeshita and his
Cabinet resign and even the prime minister's advisory panel urged
him to apologize to the public.
   Takashi Ishihara, a member of the Wisemen's Club on Political
Reform that Takeshita formed in January, said, ``It is important for
him (the prime minister) to apologize and make his responsibility
clear'' in the Recruit case.
   ``The very idea of a politician making money through stock
transaction is wrong,'' said Ishihara, chairman of Nissan Motor Co.
   The panel also urged Takeshita to accept opposition demands to
summon his predecessor, Yasuhiro Nakasone, to Parliament to testify
about his role in the affair.
   Takeshita said Friday, ``Since this problem surfaced during my
term in office I cannot turn my back on it. We must work to restore
the public trust by initiating political reforms.''
   Opposition parties have stalled parliamentary debate on the
country's budget since Wednesday when the LDP rejected their demands
that Takeshita resign or summon Nakasone to Parliament for
questioning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
