<FIRST>r a AM-ManchinImpeachment     03-18 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manchin Impeachment,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasurer Testifies at Impeachment Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Treasurer A. James Manchin
testified at his impeachment hearing Friday that he received
documents showing massive losses in the state's consolidated
investment fund but didn't pay attention to them.
   Stating repeatedly ``I'm not a financial expert,'' the two-term
Democrat said he did not understand investment reports that crossed
his desk and had no idea the fund lost $279 million until late
November or early December 1988.
   The House Judiciary Committee, which has heard more than 50 hours
of testimony in the past two weeks, is to vote next week on whether
the House of Delegates should impeach Manchin.
   If the House does so, the treasurer would be tried by the state
Senate.
   Manchin, the last witness scheduled to appear before the
committee, said he depended on his staff to handle the investment
division in his office and that then-Associate Treasurer Arnold
Margolin and then-investment director Kathy Lester kept the losses
from him.
   ``The system failed,'' Manchin said. ``The checks didn't check.
The balances didn't balance.''
   Since the losses became public, Manchin said, he has been keeping
a close eye on the investment division. But when Delegate Rod Berry
asked Manchin how much the investment division made or lost last
week, Manchin would not answer.
   ``We can get you a report on that,'' the treasurer said.
   The losses occurred when the bond market took a nosedive in April
1987, and the treasurer's office traded extensively to keep the
losses at a minimum, other witnesses have testified. Instead, the
losses continued to mount.
   Manchin also was questioned Friday about a report he said was
sent to his office that showed the investment fund losing millions
of dollars in June 1987. Manchin expressed some confusion about the
meaning of the document and why some figures were shown in
parentheses _ a common method of showing losses on financial
documents.
   Manchin said he paid no attention to the report when he received
it, even though 87 of 90 figures on it indicated losses.
   ``All these reports look alike,'' Manchin said. ``I am not a
financial expert. I hired the best management team available.''
</TEXT>
