<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w BC-SteelWars Adv26-2Takes   03-18 1127</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Steel Wars, Adv 26-2 Takes,1153</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Caterpillar, Steel Industry At Odds Over Quotas</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Feuchter lovingly taps the bright yellow
bulldozer awaiting finishing touches on the Caterpillar Inc.
production line. ``You can hardly point to a part on there that
isn't steel,'' he says.
   Steel is the backbone of Caterpillar's business, and nobody knows
it more intimately than Feuchter, who buys 500,000 tons a year of
the metal that winds up in the formidable earth-moving machines
under the CAT name.
   As it searches for the cheapest materials available, Caterpillar
finds itself at odds with its major supplier, the U.S. steel
industry, over quotas that limit imports of foreign steel.
   Twenty percent of the half-million tons of the steel Caterpillar
uses annually comes from Europe, Canada and other countries
overseas. The company joined, by a coalition of about 250 mostly
small manufacturers, is fighting efforts to extend the quotas.
   It is a fight not just about trade but about politics.
   President Bush made a campaign promise to renew the so-called
Voluntary Restraint Agreements (VRAs) when they expire Sept. 30, and
54 senators are co-sponsoring legislation to extend for five years
the VRAs, which limit the European Community and 19 other countries
to a 20 percent share of the U.S. market. Despite complaints from
the steel industry, the United States refused to subject Canada to
the VRAs in 1984.
   Bush, however, is an ardent champion of free trade and a foe of
what he calls the ``fool's gold'' of protectionism.
   Indeed, in the same letter to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., pledging to
support continuation of the VRAs, Bush also vowed to press for an
international consensus on fair trade that would eliminate the need
for the U.S. barrier.
   Even now, top-level Bush trade and economic officials are
debating internally just how long the extended VRAs should last and
what types of steel they should cover. U.S. Trade Representative
Carla Hills has echoed Bush's sentiments that the VRAs are a stopgap
and the real goal is to end the subsidies, dumping and closed
markets that distort the price of steel.
   It is the first major test of trade policy for the Bush
administration. If the United States insists on some protective
barrier to shelter its steel industry, how much force will it carry
when it insists on dismantling the barriers that protect farmers in
Europe or Japan?
   Political realities at home may force Bush, like Ronald Reagan
before him, to temper disdain for protectionism against the pressing
need to rein in the $137 billion trade deficit and bolster a vital
U.S. industry that saw 290,000 jobs disappear in the past decade.
   The U.S. steel industry is operating today at 89 percent of
capacity, rolling up profits of $3 billion in the past two years
after being staggered by losses of $12 billion in the previous five.
   Caterpillar and its allies charge the VRAs will force U.S.
companies to pay artificially high prices for the next five years,
impairing their ability to sell goods here and abroad.
   The VRAs ``cost us dearly,'' said Patrick A. Thompson, president
of Trans-Matic Inc. of Holland, Mich., and chairman of the Precision
Metalforming Association. ``If we are ever going to get the trade
deficit down, people in manufacturing are going to have to start
shipping product out of this country. But before we can do that,
we've got to have the material.''
   But the steel industry counters vehemently that what is at stake
is the survival of the American mills, still struggling to regroup
and modernize after the calamitous downturn in the first half of the
1980s.
   ``The VRAs are in the long-run interests of (American) consumers
as well as producers,'' said Alan W. Wolff, a former deputy U.S.
trade representative leading the industry fight.
   ``Obviously in the United States everyone wants to buy everything
at the lowest possible price now,'' said Wolff. But no other
industrialized country ``has considered it acceptable to lose its
self-sufficiency in steel.''
   Thomas C. Graham, president of the USS Division of USX Corp., the
biggest U.S. steel maker, put it more bluntly at a recent Washington
debate on VRAs.
   ``If we keep putzing around with this VRA question ... more of
the industry (will) liquidate, and there will be all this
handwringing about allocation,'' Graham said.
   Caterpillar and its coalition notwithstanding, Graham claimed
that ``95 percent of our customers are with us'' in support of the
import quotas.
   ``They've seen a third of the domestic steel industry liquidate
(and) they know that process can continue. It's in their enlightened
self-interest,'' said Graham, the chairman of the American Iron &amp;
Steel Institute.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A few years ago, Peoria-based Caterpillar, like the U.S. steel
industry, was on the industrial critical list. The company lost $953
million in 1982-84 and saw Japan's Komatsu pose a stiff challenge to
its world leadership in the heavy construction field.
   Big Cat battled back by restructuring factory floors, forging a
new relationship with workers, and looking for every possible way to
lower costs and stay competitive in the world marketplace. Last year
it posted profits of $616 million on record sales of $10.4 billion,
half of them abroad.
   The weaker dollar helped revive Caterpillar's fortunes, but
company officials say the recovery was also sped by radically
altering their production methods to emphasize quality and minimize
costs. Stacks of empty parts bins outside one of the Caterpillar
plants straddling the Illinois River testify to the company's
success in eliminating the need for huge stockpiles of parts.
   Feuchter, manager of central purchasing for Caterpillar's steel
division, said, ``Our chief needs are high quality materials on time
and at the right price. VRAs don't help any of that. They inhibit
our ability to shop the best way we know how.''
   While steel prices fell during the first two years under VRAs,
Timothy L. Elder, Caterpillar's manager of governmental affairs,
said, ``They were overpriced to begin with.''
   He cited a study done for the anti-VRA coalition by the Stern
Group, a trade advisory group headed by former International Trade
Commissioner Paula Stern, that concluded U.S. manufacturers paid an
average of $5 billion, or 25 percent, more for steel each year from
1969 through 1985 than their counterparts in Japan and West Germany.
   Strong worldwide demand has pushed steel prices up since 1986.
Caterpillar blames the quotas for helping push up its prices for
plate steel 17 percent a year ago, and for inducing shortages of
large tractor track shoes that are only made overseas.
   The Commerce Department allowed Caterpillar last summer to import
an extra 13,000 tons of the steel track shoes because of the short
supply.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
