<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0632EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Eastern-AssetStripping Adv19   03-18 1184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Asset Stripping, Adv 19,1219</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Papers: Bad Deals Stripped Eastern, Helped Texas Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bargain prices for coveted airport gates and
computer reservation systems. Millions in loans from a debt-swamped
airline to its growing sister. Money-losing deals to buy fuel from
the parent.
   In court papers, Eastern Airlines' recalcitrant pilots make a
strong case that Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo has plotted
to suck Eastern's blood to buoy non-union Continental Airlines, a
key issue as the saga of the strike-decimated carrier moves through
bankruptcy proceedings.
   ``Either a sophisticated asset stripping scheme is under way or
management is incompetent,'' the pilots state in documents filed in
U.S. Bankruptcy Court last week.
   The pilots cite alleged bargain sales, no-gain loans and
money-losing arrangements they say have undermined parent Texas
Air's claim that its affiliated airlines are separate entities. They
say Lorenzo's management clearly benefited Continental and Texas Air
at Eastern's detriment.
   Eastern, which was losing money long before Lorenzo arrived in
1986, says it transacted above-board, fair-market deals among
subsidiaries, with no illicit intermingling of Eastern and
Continental blood.
   Nonetheless, a 59-page court brief filed last week by the Air
Line Pilots Association provides illuminating details that at least
raise major questions about Eastern management's behavior.
   The brief culls information from Securities and Exchange
Commission filings, federal court testimony, a Transportation
Department report and company financial records to make the case
that Eastern and Continental are deeply interwoven.
   The most striking deal _ ``the red flag on the bull in the
bullring'' in the words of one aviation analyst _ was the 1987
transfer of Eastern's coveted computerized reservation system to
Continental for $100 million.
   At the time, the system was worth at least triple that amount.
Moreover, debt-swamped Eastern didn't get a $100 million cash
infusion from the deal, which it badly needed to support day-to-day
operations. Instead it got $100 million in notes bearing 6 percent
interest _ payable in full in the year 2012.
   Analysts have questioned the financial wisdom of transferring the
computerized reservation system to its new sister. Similar networks
soon after fetched $280 million, $500 million and $650 million.
   Eastern maintains it couldn't afford to upgrade its network in a
highly competitive battle for travel agents, who book tickets
through airline-run computers. Eastern says it was paying $130
million a year to operate the network, money it now pays to Texas
Air for a better product.
   The question of whether Eastern and Continental have been kept
separate is central to the bankruptcy proceedings.
   A judge ultimately could decide whether Lorenzo allowed Eastern
to languish and refused to merge the two subsidiaries in an attempt
to destroy Eastern's unions. Texas Air wants to avoid placing its
assets on the line to cover Eastern's more than $3 billion in
liabilities.
   ``By keeping the companies separate, Lorenzo doesn't get the two
groups together to be unionized,'' said a New York aviation lawyer
who asked not to be identified. ``If he put the two together he
would face a situation where if he allowed enough parity of
employees that would force an election.
   ``Then Lorenzo has a completely unionized property, which is what
he got out of five years ago.''
   The pilots' court brief also alleges the following action damaged
Eastern:
   _Eastern loaned $40 million to Continental last spring at the
same time it was seeking an Internal Revenue Service waiver on a
$105 million contribution to its pension fund. Eastern says the loan
was repaid.
   _For almost two years Eastern failed to demand a non-interest
bearing $16 million payment due for merger-related expenses from
Texas Air. The inaction cost the airline about $2.8 million a year
in lost interest earnings. Eastern called it a ``bookkeeping
transaction'' that has since been paid.
   _In March 1987, Eastern paid Texas Air $25 million for a note
worth $30 million owned by nearly bankrupt People Express, which
Texas Air had previously acquired. Texas Air made $4.4 million on
the deal. The pilots called it a senseless investment since People
Express had no creditworthiness and Eastern needed to conserve cash.
   _Eastern paid $22 million to Continental for strike-related
services in December 1987 and another $19 million last fall for
similar services that have not been used. Eastern maintains the
money was well-spent.
   _Continental, the pilots claim, disproportionate gained from a
merger of sales offices with Eastern in January 1987. Eastern
brought in 166 offices while Continental contributed 27. The
arrangement was dissolved last December.
   _Continental paid $11 million to Eastern for 11 Newark
International Airport gates allegedly worth twice as much. The court
papers compare the deal with Eastern's 1986 sale of eight Charlotte,
N.C., gates to Piedmont Airlines for $25 million. Eastern says it
got the market price.
   _A fuel purchase agreement with Texas Air costs Eastern about $18
million annually but provides no apparent savings, the papers state.
Eastern claims it saves $6 million a year. Texas Air claims the
arrangement merges purchases of Eastern and Continental, giving them
greater clout with suppliers.
   _The pending sale of the Northeast shuttle to Donald Trump for
$365 million will reduce Eastern's cash flow by $30 million to $40
million, the pilots say. The airline says sale of the shuttle,
despite its profitability, is necessary for the airline's survival.
   The pilots claim downsizing Eastern last year by closing its
Kansas City. Mo., hub and selling planes, routes and airport gates
as part of $130 million in asset sales has hurt profitability while
benefiting Continental. They also say most of Eastern's directors
and managers used to work at Texas Air, Continental or both _ and
don't have Eastern's best interests in mind.
   Another key issue involves Eastern's pension obligations _ put at
$320 million by the company but $750 million by the federal Pension
Benefit Guarantee Corporation. Under federal law, Texas Air and
Continental could be held liable for the total underfunding of
Eastern's pension plans.
   If Eastern fails to make a $100 million payment due in September,
lawyers said, the government could tap money from elsewhere in the
Texas Air structure. To guarantee payment, Eastern may sell more
assets.
   The pilots' court papers ask Judge Burton R. Lifland to appoint a
trustee to run Eastern during bankruptcy proceedings, charging that
Lorenzo would continue dismantling Eastern and try to break its
unions, as he did after taking Continental into bankruptcy in 1983.
   ``It may not win over the long run but it certainly puts a lot of
flies in the ointment in terms of trying to get the assets sold
piecemeal,'' said Louis Marckesano, an analyst with Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
   But lawyers said obtaining a trustee is difficult and may be
viewed by Lifland as unnecessary. Moreover, the judge may not view
Eastern management's sale of assets and other actions as
irresponsible.
   ``These asset sales have kept Eastern in business,'' Eastern
spokesman Robin Matell said. ``Without these sales, this company
would have gone belly-up a long time ago.''
   End adv for Sunday, March 19
</TEXT>
