<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv18-19   03-18 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 18-19,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions Adv 18-19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health Perils of the Pits: Pencil Stabs, Hypertension, `Your Normal
Stuff'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs for UNDATED item on Business Enterprise Digest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As veteran Fire Department paramedics working some
of Chicago's meanest streets, Kevin Roche and Joe Guzzardo thought
they'd seen just about everything. Then they they took part-time
jobs staffing the medical office at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``The one I'll never forget,'' said Guzzardo, ``is the time a guy
came in here with part of a pencil sticking out of his chest. I
mean, it gets rough in the (trading) pits every so often, and we get
lots of guys stabbed with pencils.
   ``Hands are pretty common and every once in a while, a guy will
get stuck in the face. But this guy got it in the chest and the poor
guy was panicking so much, we pulled it out ourselves instead of
sending him over to the hospital.
   ``And as soon as we finished bandaging him up,'' Guzzardo said,
``he puts his jacket back on and went back to trade.''
   Roche nods, then adds, ``Thank God they're making pencils out of
graphite.
   ``Because if they were still using lead, we'd have lost a few
guys.''
   To be truthful, a typical day at the Board of Trade's medical
office, located just a few stops down the marble-paneled hallway
from the coat room of the sprawling futures market, is less like an
episode of the television series ``M.A.S.H'' than a commercial for
Maytag appliances.
   An average of 10 to 15 traders find their way into the office
each day, about half for what amounts to regularly scheduled
maintenance and the other half for ``cuts and bruises, flu, your
normal stuff,'' said Roche.
   ``We monitor about 200 guys on a regular basis...blood pressure,
headaches and dizziness, the occasional diabetic. The funny thing,''
he said, ``is that people probably guess with all the pressure and
high stakes around this place, we'd get lots of guys coming
in...hyperventilating and such.
   ``But I've been here since they opened the office and never once
has a guy come in here, sweating or bug-eyed or anything and said,
`Jeez, I just lost my shirt.'
   ``Most of the guys with a history of high blood pressure or heart
troubles are under the regular care of the doctor. We see them at
the beginning of the day or the end,'' he said. ``You can never get
a feel for what's going on in the pits by what happens in here.''
   The medical office was created in 1978 in case of health
emergencies at the fast-growing exchange, a leading U.S. center for
trading futures contracts in items that range from grains to
soybeans to Treasury bonds.
   Today if offers a range of services and equipment far beyond its
humble origins. In the beginning, Roche notes, pointing to a small
photo on the wall, the ``office'' was a cabinet with a single oxygen
tank inside.
   Today, it boasts emergency life-support and state-of-the-art
heart and respiratory monitoring systems and is staffed by six
Chicago Fire Department paramedics working on a revolving basis
during their 36 hours between shifts.
   Despite having worked at the Board of Trade for 10 years, Roche
said he does little other than keeping abreast of how some of the
commodities traded there might be doing _ strictly for the sake of
conversation _ and ``doesn't dabble.''
   ``No way,'' he said. ``You might hear somebody say something
about this or that or the other, but it's something I'd never get
into.
   ``Look,'' he added, ``I've got more than enough stress in my
regular job.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
