<FIRST>r f BC-WeeklyCommodities 1stAdd   03-18 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Commodities, 1st Add,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: regular job.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week:
   Soybean and corn futures prices advanced, but wheat slipped on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in March settled Friday at $4.34 a bushel.
down from $4.36 a week earlier; March corn climbed to $2.78\ a
bushel from $2.75{; March oats rose to $2.08 a bushel from $2.07;
and soybeans rose to $7.69 a bushel from $7.57.
   Livestock and pork futures mostly were lower at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   April live cattle was unchanged at 78.05 cents a pound; March
feeder cattle slipped to 79.67 cents a pound from 81.25 cents; April
live hogs were 42.72 cents a pound; down from 43.65 cents; and March
frozen pork bellies slipped to 36.95 cents a pound from 38.45 cents.
   Gold futures declined but silver futures were higher on New
York's Commodity Exchange.
   April gold slipped to $393.60 a troy ounce from $389.30; May
silver rose to $6.195 a troy ounce from $6.150.
   Energy futures made impressive gains on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for April delivery zoomed to
$20.33 a barrel from $18.50; April heating oil climbed to 53.57
cents a gallon from 51.19 cents; and April unleaded gasoline rose to
55.62 cents a gallon from 51.78 cents.
</TEXT>
