<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Sears-Women'sWear     03-18 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears-Women's Wear,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears First: Outside Designer to Develop Three New Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail giant Sears, Roebuck and Co., in the midst
of an overhaul of its operation, has for the first time signed up an
outside designer to develop three new lines of house-brand women's
wear.
   The move is ``limited in scope,'' said Sears spokeswoman Kathy
Gucfa, but has ``tremendous potential.
   Sears occasionally had used outside consultants in the past, she
said, but never to the extent of having them handle the entire
project.
   ``It's an indication we're more open to some fresh outside
ideas,'' Ms. Gucfa said. ``We're looking at difference approaches to
our business.''
   Sears tends to be better known for its durable goods than for
fashions.
   The company's recent restructuring moves _ ranging from the
marketing of its landmark Sears Tower, the world's tallest building,
to everyday low prices systemwide _ include a move toward increased
use of outside name brands.
   But that move was not so strong in clothing departments, Ms.
Gucfa said.
   ``The whole store still has more private that national brands,
but in apparel even more so,'' she said.
   The new lines will be private-label merchandise from Associated
Merchandising Co. of New York, owned by a group of the nation's
largest department stores.
   Ms. Gucfa said the new sportswear lines from AMC are to include
Premises, fashionable separates at ``better prices''; Middlebrook
Park, offering more traditional styles; and a third line, not yet
named more, of larger apparel.
   While Premises is a little more upscale than the clothing
traditionally offered Sears' women customers, ``none of it is a
departure for us,'' she said. ``It's still Sears.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
